{"parentUuid":"1d5b7cca-f312-4f71-95d7-42355e9c3e91","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"53f5148a-6791-4be6-a2fc-f4eaf65be586","agentId":"aab619a6f776136ee","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01HkLCRbwroBdUNwVH3nZb8w","type":"tool_result","content":"<system-reminder>[Truncated: PARTIAL view — showing lines 1-1202 of 2430 total (42936 tokens, cap 25000). Call Read with offset=1203 limit=1202 for the next page, or Grep to find a specific section. Do NOT answer from this page alone if the answer may be further in the file.]</system-reminder>\n\n1\tThis file is a merged representation of a subset of the codebase, containing specifically included files, combined into a single document by Repomix.\n2\tThe content has been processed where content has been compressed (code blocks are separated by ⋮---- delimiter).\n3\t\n4\t<file_summary>\n5\tThis section contains a summary of this file.\n6\t\n7\t<purpose>\n8\tThis file contains a packed representation of a subset of the repository's contents that is considered the most important context.\n9\tIt is designed to be easily consumable by AI systems for analysis, code review,\n10\tor other automated processes.\n11\t</purpose>\n12\t\n13\t<file_format>\n14\tThe content is organized as follows:\n15\t1. This summary section\n16\t2. Repository information\n17\t3. Directory structure\n18\t4. Repository files (if enabled)\n19\t5. Multiple file entries, each consisting of:\n20\t  - File path as an attribute\n21\t  - Full contents of the file\n22\t</file_format>\n23\t\n24\t<usage_guidelines>\n25\t- This file should be treated as read-only. Any changes should be made to the\n26\t  original repository files, not this packed version.\n27\t- When processing this file, use the file path to distinguish\n28\t  between different files in the repository.\n29\t- Be aware that this file may contain sensitive information. Handle it with\n30\t  the same level of security as you would the original repository.\n31\t</usage_guidelines>\n32\t\n33\t<notes>\n34\t- Some files may have been excluded based on .gitignore rules and Repomix's configuration\n35\t- Binary files are not included in this packed representation. Please refer to the Repository Structure section for a complete list of file paths, including binary files\n36\t- Only files matching these patterns are included: src/**, alembic/versions/**, CLAUDE.md, PROJECT.md, pyproject.toml\n37\t- Files matching patterns in .gitignore are excluded\n38\t- Files matching default ignore patterns are excluded\n39\t- Content has been compressed - code blocks are separated by ⋮---- delimiter\n40\t- Files are sorted by Git change count (files with more changes are at the bottom)\n41\t</notes>\n42\t\n43\t</file_summary>\n44\t\n45\t<directory_structure>\n46\talembic/versions/0001_create_api_keys_and_events.py\n47\talembic/versions/0002_create_usage_rollup_backfill.py\n48\talembic/versions/0003_create_quotas_and_api_key_scope.py\n49\tCLAUDE.md\n50\tPROJECT.md\n51\tpyproject.toml\n52\tsrc/__init__.py\n53\tsrc/api/__init__.py\n54\tsrc/api/errors.py\n55\tsrc/api/middleware.py\n56\tsrc/api/README.md\n57\tsrc/api/routes/__init__.py\n58\tsrc/api/routes/events.py\n59\tsrc/api/routes/health.py\n60\tsrc/api/routes/quotas.py\n61\tsrc/api/routes/usage.py\n62\tsrc/api/schemas/__init__.py\n63\tsrc/api/schemas/events.py\n64\tsrc/api/schemas/quotas.py\n65\tsrc/api/schemas/usage.py\n66\tsrc/auth/__init__.py\n67\tsrc/auth/api_key.py\n68\tsrc/auth/rate_limit.py\n69\tsrc/auth/README.md\n70\tsrc/config/__init__.py\n71\tsrc/config/README.md\n72\tsrc/config/secrets.py\n73\tsrc/config/settings.py\n74\tsrc/crypto/__init__.py\n75\tsrc/crypto/README.md\n76\tsrc/db/__init__.py\n77\tsrc/db/README.md\n78\tsrc/db/session.py\n79\tsrc/logging/__init__.py\n80\tsrc/logging/middleware.py\n81\tsrc/logging/README.md\n82\tsrc/main.py\n83\tsrc/observability/__init__.py\n84\tsrc/observability/otel.py\n85\tsrc/observability/README.md\n86\tsrc/observability/sentry.py\n87\tsrc/README.md\n88\tsrc/repositories/__init__.py\n89\tsrc/repositories/api_keys_repo.py\n90\tsrc/repositories/events_repo.py\n91\tsrc/repositories/quotas_repo.py\n92\tsrc/repositories/README.md\n93\tsrc/repositories/usage_repo.py\n94\tsrc/services/__init__.py\n95\tsrc/services/events_service.py\n96\tsrc/services/quota_service.py\n97\tsrc/services/README.md\n98\tsrc/services/time_windows.py\n99\tsrc/services/usage_service.py\n100\t</directory_structure>\n101\t\n102\t<files>\n103\tThis section contains the contents of the repository's files.\n104\t\n105\t<file path=\"alembic/versions/0001_create_api_keys_and_events.py\">\n106\t\"\"\"create api_keys and events\n107\t\n108\tA create-migration: `down` drops both tables in FK-safe order. Reversibility\n109\tkind is schema + constraints (row survival across `down` is undefined by\n110\tdefinition for a create-migration — `down` drops the tables); AC-MIGRATION-1\n111\tasserts `up -> down -> up` restores the schema and re-enforces every\n112\tCHECK/FK/UNIQUE/NOT NULL identically.\n113\t\n114\tRevision ID: 0001\n115\tRevises:\n116\tCreate Date: 2026-01-01 00:00:00\n117\t\n118\t\"\"\"\n119\t⋮----\n120\trevision: str = \"0001\"\n121\tdown_revision: Union[str, None] = None\n122\tbranch_labels: Union[str, Sequence[str], None] = None\n123\tdepends_on: Union[str, Sequence[str], None] = None\n124\t⋮----\n125\tdef upgrade() -> None\n126\t⋮----\n127\t\"\"\"Create `api_keys` (the tenant/credential table) and `events` (the\n128\t    append-only ingest log), with the UNIQUE constraint that backs the\n129\t    idempotency guarantee and the index the backfill/operational queries need.\n130\t    \"\"\"\n131\t⋮----\n132\t# Row-level security backstop (defense-in-depth behind the application-level\n133\t# api_key_id scoping every repository query applies — plan §\"Row-level security\").\n134\t⋮----\n135\tdef downgrade() -> None\n136\t⋮----\n137\t\"\"\"Drop `events` then `api_keys` (FK-safe order). A create-migration's\n138\t    `down` is a schema-only rollback — row survival is not asserted here.\"\"\"\n139\t</file>\n140\t\n141\t<file path=\"alembic/versions/0002_create_usage_rollup_backfill.py\">\n142\t\"\"\"create usage_rollup and backfill from events\n143\t\n144\tAn expand + backfill migration. `up` creates `usage_rollup` then derives it\n145\tfrom the existing `events` rows via `GROUP BY`; `down` drops only\n146\t`usage_rollup` and leaves `events` untouched. Reversibility kind: the seeded\n147\t`events` rows are preserved across `up -> down -> up` (this migration never\n148\tmutates `events`), and `usage_rollup` is deterministically re-derived from\n149\tthem each `up` — so `down` \"losing\" the rollup is expected (it is pure\n150\tderivation, rebuildable from the source of truth). AC-MIGRATION asserts this\n151\tround-trip on a prod-shaped seeded dataset.\n152\t\n153\tRevision ID: 0002\n154\tRevises: 0001\n155\tCreate Date: 2026-01-02 00:00:00\n156\t\n157\t\"\"\"\n158\t⋮----\n159\trevision: str = \"0002\"\n160\tdown_revision: Union[str, None] = \"0001\"\n161\tbranch_labels: Union[str, Sequence[str], None] = None\n162\tdepends_on: Union[str, Sequence[str], None] = None\n163\t⋮----\n164\tdef upgrade() -> None\n165\t⋮----\n166\t\"\"\"Create `usage_rollup` and backfill it from `events` via a single\n167\t    deterministic `GROUP BY` aggregate.\n168\t\n169\t    Safe on a live system in the classic expand/backfill sense (events\n170\t    written *during* the backfill wouldn't be missed) because this is the\n171\t    first deploy with no pre-existing traffic and `deploy.yml` runs\n172\t    snapshot -> migrate -> roll out, so migrations complete before any\n173\t    dual-writing code serves traffic (see the plan's expand/contract note).\n174\t    \"\"\"\n175\t⋮----\n176\t# Same RLS backstop as `events` (plan §\"Row-level security\") — a policy on\n177\t# the derived aggregate too, since it holds the same per-tenant totals.\n178\t⋮----\n179\tdef downgrade() -> None\n180\t⋮----\n181\t\"\"\"Drop `usage_rollup` only — `events`, the source of truth, is untouched\n182\t    (so `up` afterward re-derives an identical rollup from the same rows).\"\"\"\n183\t</file>\n184\t\n185\t<file path=\"alembic/versions/0003_create_quotas_and_api_key_scope.py\">\n186\t\"\"\"create quotas table and api_keys.scope column\n187\t\n188\tOne expand-only revision covering two changes (plan: \"ONE expand-only\n189\tmigration\"):\n190\t\n191\t- `quotas`: a create-migration. `down` drops the table, so row survival\n192\t  across `down` is undefined by definition — reversibility kind is\n193\t  schema + constraints only. `up -> down -> up` must restore the schema and\n194\t  re-enforce every PK/FK/CHECK identically (AC16).\n195\t- `api_keys.scope`: an expand on a populated table (`DEFAULT 'ingest'`\n196\t  backfills existing rows for free, no data migration needed, safe on a live\n197\t  table). Pre-existing `api_keys` rows survive `up -> down -> up` unchanged\n198\t  except the `scope` column resets to its default on `down` — the defined\n199\t  expand/contract contract of an add-column, not data loss of a populated\n200\t  business column (AC16).\n201\t\n202\tRevision ID: 0003\n203\tRevises: 0002\n204\tCreate Date: 2026-07-08 00:00:00\n205\t\n206\t\"\"\"\n207\t⋮----\n208\trevision: str = \"0003\"\n209\tdown_revision: Union[str, None] = \"0002\"\n210\tbranch_labels: Union[str, Sequence[str], None] = None\n211\tdepends_on: Union[str, Sequence[str], None] = None\n212\t⋮----\n213\tdef upgrade() -> None\n214\t⋮----\n215\t\"\"\"Create `quotas` (per-tenant per-customer per-metric usage caps) and add\n216\t    `api_keys.scope` (authorization attribute: `'ingest'` default, `'admin'`\n217\t    elevated for `PUT /v1/quotas`).\"\"\"\n218\t⋮----\n219\t# Row-level security backstop (mirrors events/usage_rollup — plan\n220\t# §\"Row-level security\"); the primary control is the explicit\n221\t# `api_key_id = :api_key_id` filter every quotas query already applies.\n222\t⋮----\n223\t# FORCE so the policy binds even for the table OWNER. The migration job\n224\t# resolves the DB URL through the same secrets facade the app uses\n225\t# (alembic/env.py -> get_database_url -> the meterly_app credential in\n226\t# Secrets Manager), so meterly_app — which holds CREATE ON SCHEMA public —\n227\t# is the table owner. A table owner bypasses non-FORCE RLS regardless of\n228\t# NOBYPASSRLS, which would leave quotas_tenant_isolation inert for the app\n229\t# role (plan Open Question 2). FORCE makes the backstop effective; the app\n230\t# path is unaffected because every quotas access runs inside\n231\t# scoped_transaction, which SET LOCAL app.current_api_key_id so the policy's\n232\t# USING/WITH CHECK predicate passes for the caller's own rows.\n233\t⋮----\n234\t# `DEFAULT 'ingest'` backfills every existing row with no data migration\n235\t# (Postgres 11+ does not rewrite the table for a non-volatile default),\n236\t# so this is safe to run against a live, populated api_keys table.\n237\t⋮----\n238\tdef downgrade() -> None\n239\t⋮----\n240\t\"\"\"Drop `quotas` (schema-only rollback — row survival not asserted) and\n241\t    remove `api_keys.scope` (the pre-existing rows and their other columns\n242\t    survive; only the `scope` column itself disappears).\"\"\"\n243\t</file>\n244\t\n245\t<file path=\"pyproject.toml\">\n246\t[tool.poetry]\n247\tname = \"meterly\"\n248\tversion = \"0.1.0\"\n249\tdescription = \"Usage-metering ingestion API: idempotent event ingest + aggregated usage query.\"\n250\tauthors = [\"Meterly Engineering\"]\n251\treadme = \"README.md\"\n252\tpackage-mode = true\n253\tpackages = [{ include = \"src\" }]\n254\t\n255\t[tool.poetry.dependencies]\n256\tpython = \"^3.12\"\n257\tfastapi = \"0.133.0\"\n258\tstarlette = \"1.3.1\"\n259\tuvicorn = { version = \"0.34.0\", extras = [\"standard\"] }\n260\tgunicorn = \"23.0.0\"\n261\tpydantic = \"2.10.4\"\n262\tpydantic-settings = \"2.7.1\"\n263\tsqlalchemy = \"2.0.36\"\n264\tasyncpg = \"0.30.0\"\n265\talembic = \"1.14.0\"\n266\targon2-cffi = \"23.1.0\"\n267\tredis = \"5.2.1\"\n268\tstructlog = \"24.4.0\"\n269\tsentry-sdk = \"2.19.2\"\n270\topentelemetry-sdk = \"1.29.0\"\n271\topentelemetry-instrumentation-fastapi = \"0.50b0\"\n272\topentelemetry-exporter-otlp = \"1.29.0\"\n273\tboto3 = \"1.35.90\"\n274\t\n275\t[tool.poetry.group.dev.dependencies]\n276\tpytest = \"8.3.4\"\n277\tpytest-asyncio = \"0.25.0\"\n278\tpytest-cov = \"6.0.0\"\n279\thttpx = \"0.28.1\"\n280\ttestcontainers = { version = \"4.9.0\", extras = [\"postgres\"] }\n281\thypothesis = \"6.123.2\"\n282\t\n283\t[build-system]\n284\trequires = [\"poetry-core>=1.9.0\"]\n285\tbuild-backend = \"poetry.core.masonry.api\"\n286\t\n287\t[tool.pytest.ini_options]\n288\ttestpaths = [\"tests\"]\n289\tasyncio_mode = \"auto\"\n290\t\n291\t[tool.coverage.run]\n292\tbranch = true\n293\tsource = [\"src\"]\n294\t</file>\n295\t\n296\t<file path=\"src/__init__.py\">\n297\t\"\"\"Meterly — usage-metering ingestion API (event ingest + aggregated usage query).\"\"\"\n298\t</file>\n299\t\n300\t<file path=\"src/api/__init__.py\">\n301\t\"\"\"HTTP boundary: routes, request/response schemas, middleware, and the error envelope.\"\"\"\n302\t</file>\n303\t\n304\t<file path=\"src/api/routes/__init__.py\">\n305\t\"\"\"FastAPI routers for the events, usage, and health endpoints.\"\"\"\n306\t</file>\n307\t\n308\t<file path=\"src/api/routes/events.py\">\n309\t\"\"\"`POST /v1/events` — record a metered event, idempotent on `idempotency_key`.\n310\t\n311\tEdge behavior (security headers, CORS, body-size guard, Tier-1 throttle) is\n312\tinherited from the middleware stack; this route only wires\n313\tauth -> Tier-2 throttle -> schema validation -> service.\n314\t\"\"\"\n315\t⋮----\n316\trouter = APIRouter(tags=[\"events\"])\n317\t⋮----\n318\t\"\"\"Compose auth then the Tier-2 per-key throttle, in that order.\n319\t\n320\t    A single dependency function pins the ordering FastAPI resolves\n321\t    dependencies in: `require_api_key` must complete (and thus populate\n322\t    `principal`) before `enforce_tier2_rate_limit` can key its bucket on it.\n323\t    \"\"\"\n324\t⋮----\n325\t\"\"\"Record `payload` as a new event, or return the original result if\n326\t    `idempotency_key` was already seen for this caller (200, no-op).\"\"\"\n327\toutcome = await create_event(principal, payload)\n328\t</file>\n329\t\n330\t<file path=\"src/api/routes/health.py\">\n331\t\"\"\"Liveness and readiness endpoints.\n332\t\n333\tSplit per `containerization-conventions`: `/health` is liveness (process is\n334\tup, no dependency checks — must pass with no database reachable, which is\n335\twhat the local smoke check and `import src.main` build-fallback rely on);\n336\t`/health/ready` is readiness (checks the database and migration head) and is\n337\twhat the ALB target group and the canary soak probe, so traffic is gated on\n338\treal dependency health.\n339\t\"\"\"\n340\t⋮----\n341\trouter = APIRouter(tags=[\"health\"])\n342\t⋮----\n343\t@router.get(\"/health\")\n344\tasync def liveness() -> dict\n345\t⋮----\n346\t\"\"\"Liveness probe: returns 200 whenever the process is up. No I/O, no dependencies.\"\"\"\n347\t⋮----\n348\tasync def _current_migration_is_head() -> bool\n349\t⋮----\n350\t\"\"\"Compare the database's applied Alembic revision against the code's\n351\t    migration head — a mismatch means the deployed image is ahead of (or\n352\t    behind) the schema it expects, which readiness should fail on.\"\"\"\n353\t⋮----\n354\tscript_directory = ScriptDirectory.from_config(Config(\"alembic.ini\"))\n355\texpected_head = script_directory.get_current_head()\n356\t⋮----\n357\tresult = await connection.execute(text(\"SELECT version_num FROM alembic_version\"))\n358\tapplied_revision = result.scalar_one_or_none()\n359\t⋮----\n360\t@router.get(\"/health/ready\")\n361\tasync def readiness() -> JSONResponse\n362\t⋮----\n363\t\"\"\"Readiness probe: 200 only if the database is reachable and at the\n364\t    expected migration head.\n365\t\n366\t    A readiness endpoint that returns 200 unconditionally defeats the canary\n367\t    health gate (`containerization-conventions`), so this performs a real,\n368\t    fast `SELECT 1` plus a migration-head comparison rather than a static\n369\t    response.\n370\t    \"\"\"\n371\t⋮----\n372\tat_head = await _current_migration_is_head()\n373\texcept Exception:  # noqa: BLE001 - readiness must report, never raise\n374\tat_head = False\n375\t</file>\n376\t\n377\t<file path=\"src/api/routes/quotas.py\">\n378\t\"\"\"`PUT /v1/quotas` — admin-scoped create-or-replace of a per-customer,\n379\tper-metric usage cap.\n380\t\n381\tEdge behavior (security headers, CORS, body-size guard, Tier-1 throttle) is\n382\tinherited from the middleware stack; this route wires\n383\tauth -> Tier-2 throttle -> admin-scope check -> schema validation -> service,\n384\tmirroring the `events`/`usage` routes' sibling `_require_authenticated_and_throttled`\n385\tpattern (kept per-route, not shared, per the existing convention).\n386\t\"\"\"\n387\t⋮----\n388\trouter = APIRouter(tags=[\"quotas\"])\n389\tlogger = get_logger(service=\"meterly\")\n390\t⋮----\n391\t_ADMIN_SCOPE = \"admin\"\n392\t⋮----\n393\t\"\"\"Compose auth, then the Tier-2 per-key throttle, then the admin-scope\n394\t    gate, in that order — mirrors `src/api/routes/events.py`'s dependency\n395\t    chain, extended with the function-level authorization check this route\n396\t    alone requires (ASVS 8.2.1).\n397\t    \"\"\"\n398\t⋮----\n399\t\"\"\"Create or replace the cap for `(customer_id, metric)` under the\n400\t    caller's own tenant — 201 on create, 200 on replace.\"\"\"\n401\toutcome = await upsert_tenant_quota(principal, payload)\n402\t</file>\n403\t\n404\t<file path=\"src/api/routes/usage.py\">\n405\t\"\"\"`GET /v1/usage` — the aggregated usage counter for a customer/metric/window.\"\"\"\n406\t⋮----\n407\trouter = APIRouter(tags=[\"usage\"])\n408\t⋮----\n409\t\"\"\"Compose auth then the Tier-2 per-key throttle, in that order (mirrors\n410\t    `src/api/routes/events.py` — kept as a sibling, not a shared import, so\n411\t    each route's dependency chain stays independently readable).\"\"\"\n412\t⋮----\n413\t\"\"\"Return the aggregated `{total_quantity, event_count}` for the caller's\n414\t    own `(customer_id, metric, window)` bucket. A bucket with no data returns\n415\t    zeros with 200, never 404.\"\"\"\n416\t</file>\n417\t\n418\t<file path=\"src/api/schemas/__init__.py\">\n419\t\"\"\"Pydantic request/response schemas — the boundary validation contracts.\"\"\"\n420\t</file>\n421\t\n422\t<file path=\"src/api/schemas/events.py\">\n423\t\"\"\"Validation contract for `POST /v1/events`.\n424\t\n425\tEvery field the client may set is bounded by an anchored allowlist regex or a\n426\tstrict numeric range (`code-standards` input-validation invariant); `api_key_id`,\n427\t`event_time`, and `window_start` are deliberately absent from this schema — the\n428\tserver sets them from the authenticated principal and the receive time, never\n429\tfrom client input (ASVS 15.3.3 mass-assignment protection, threat T2/E3 in the\n430\tplan's STRIDE model).\n431\t\"\"\"\n432\t⋮----\n433\tCustomerId = constr(pattern=r\"^[A-Za-z0-9_.:-]{1,128}$\")\n434\tMetric = constr(pattern=r\"^[A-Za-z0-9_.:-]{1,64}$\")\n435\tIdempotencyKey = constr(pattern=r\"^[A-Za-z0-9_-]{1,200}$\")\n436\tQuantity = condecimal(gt=Decimal(0), le=Decimal(\"1e12\"), max_digits=20, decimal_places=6)\n437\t⋮----\n438\tclass EventCreateRequest(BaseModel)\n439\t⋮----\n440\t\"\"\"The client-supplied body of `POST /v1/events`.\n441\t\n442\t    `extra='forbid'` rejects any unknown field outright — this is the\n443\t    mass-assignment defense: even if a client sends `api_key_id` or\n444\t    `event_time`, the request is rejected rather than silently ignored, so\n445\t    there is no ambiguity about what the server actually used.\n446\t    \"\"\"\n447\t⋮----\n448\tmodel_config = ConfigDict(extra=\"forbid\")\n449\t⋮----\n450\tcustomer_id: CustomerId\n451\tmetric: Metric\n452\tquantity: Quantity\n453\tidempotency_key: IdempotencyKey\n454\t⋮----\n455\tclass EventResponse(BaseModel)\n456\t⋮----\n457\t\"\"\"The minimal response field set for an event (ASVS 15.3.1) — never a raw ORM row.\"\"\"\n458\t⋮----\n459\tevent_id: int\n460\tcustomer_id: str\n461\tmetric: str\n462\tquantity: Decimal\n463\twindow_start: str\n464\tidempotent_replay: bool\n465\t</file>\n466\t\n467\t<file path=\"src/api/schemas/quotas.py\">\n468\t\"\"\"Validation contract for `PUT /v1/quotas`.\n469\t\n470\t`customer_id`/`metric` reuse the exact anchored allowlists `src/api/schemas/events.py`\n471\talready validates against (the same identifiers, same sinks) — kept as separate\n472\t`constr` instances here rather than a cross-module import so this schema stays a\n473\tself-contained boundary contract (plan's validation-contract table). `api_key_id`\n474\tand `scope` are deliberately absent: the server sets `api_key_id` from the\n475\tauthenticated principal and never accepts a client-supplied `scope`, which is\n476\tthe mass-assignment defense against writing another tenant's cap or\n477\tself-elevating privilege (ASVS 15.3.3, threat T3/E2 in the plan's STRIDE model).\n478\t\"\"\"\n479\t⋮----\n480\tCustomerId = constr(pattern=r\"^[A-Za-z0-9_.:-]{1,128}$\")\n481\tMetric = constr(pattern=r\"^[A-Za-z0-9_.:-]{1,64}$\")\n482\t# BIGINT-safe upper bound: guards against an absurd/overflowing value reaching\n483\t# the BIGINT column or the R+Q>L comparison (plan's DoS row on limit_per_window).\n484\tLimitPerWindow = conint(ge=1, le=10**15)\n485\t⋮----\n486\tclass QuotaPutRequest(BaseModel)\n487\t⋮----\n488\t\"\"\"The client-supplied body of `PUT /v1/quotas`.\n489\t\n490\t    `extra='forbid'` rejects any unknown field outright, including a\n491\t    client-supplied `api_key_id` or `scope` — the create-or-replace identity\n492\t    is exactly `(customer_id, metric)`, resolved against the authenticated\n493\t    principal's own `api_key_id` by the service layer, never the request body.\n494\t    \"\"\"\n495\t⋮----\n496\tmodel_config = ConfigDict(extra=\"forbid\")\n497\t⋮----\n498\tcustomer_id: CustomerId\n499\tmetric: Metric\n500\tlimit_per_window: LimitPerWindow\n501\t⋮----\n502\tclass QuotaResponse(BaseModel)\n503\t⋮----\n504\t\"\"\"The minimal response field set for a quota (ASVS 15.3.1) — echoes only\n505\t    what the caller supplied, never the full `quotas` row (`api_key_id`,\n506\t    `created_at`, `updated_at` stay internal).\"\"\"\n507\t⋮----\n508\tcustomer_id: str\n509\tmetric: str\n510\tlimit_per_window: int\n511\t</file>\n512\t\n513\t<file path=\"src/api/schemas/usage.py\">\n514\t\"\"\"Validation contract for `GET /v1/usage`.\n515\t\n516\t`window` must be a timezone-aware ISO-8601 timestamp within `[now-90d, now+1h]`;\n517\ta naive datetime (no offset) is rejected rather than silently assumed-UTC, since\n518\tguessing wrong would silently misattribute a bucket.\n519\t\"\"\"\n520\t⋮----\n521\t_MAX_WINDOW_LOOKBACK = timedelta(days=90)\n522\t_MAX_WINDOW_LOOKAHEAD = timedelta(hours=1)\n523\t⋮----\n524\tclass UsageQueryParams(BaseModel)\n525\t⋮----\n526\t\"\"\"The three required query parameters of `GET /v1/usage`, validated as a\n527\t    single boundary schema rather than three ad-hoc query-param checks.\"\"\"\n528\t⋮----\n529\tmodel_config = ConfigDict(extra=\"forbid\")\n530\t⋮----\n531\tcustomer_id: CustomerId\n532\tmetric: Metric\n533\twindow: AwareDatetime\n534\t⋮----\n535\t@field_validator(\"window\")\n536\t@classmethod\n537\t    def _window_within_supported_range(cls, value: datetime) -> datetime\n538\t⋮----\n539\t\"\"\"Reject a `window` timestamp outside the supported query range.\n540\t\n541\t        Pydantic's `AwareDatetime` already rejects naive datetimes; this\n542\t        validator adds the `[now-90d, now+1h]` bound so a caller can't probe\n543\t        arbitrarily far into the past (unbounded query cost) or the future\n544\t        (nothing to aggregate yet).\n545\t        \"\"\"\n546\tnow = datetime.now(timezone.utc)\n547\tearliest = now - _MAX_WINDOW_LOOKBACK\n548\tlatest = now + _MAX_WINDOW_LOOKAHEAD\n549\t⋮----\n550\tclass UsageResponse(BaseModel)\n551\t⋮----\n552\t\"\"\"The minimal response field set for a usage query (ASVS 15.3.1).\"\"\"\n553\t⋮----\n554\tcustomer_id: str\n555\tmetric: str\n556\twindow_start: str\n557\ttotal_quantity: Decimal\n558\tevent_count: int\n559\t</file>\n560\t\n561\t<file path=\"src/auth/__init__.py\">\n562\t\"\"\"Auth facade — `require_api_key` is the only guard route handlers depend on.\n563\t\n564\tResolves the exact tension the plan calls out: Argon2id is intentionally slow\n565\t(tens of ms), so running it on every request at the target 500 req/s would\n566\tblow the ingest p95 budget. An in-process verification cache, keyed by the\n567\ttoken's public `key_id` and guarded by a constant-time digest comparison\n568\t(ASVS 11.2.4 — in-scope L3), lets a repeat caller on the same task skip the\n569\tArgon2id verify after the first request while the durable at-rest store stays\n570\tArgon2id-only. See the plan's \"Argon2id-vs-p95 tension\" section for the full\n571\ttradeoff writeup, including the accepted ~5 min revocation-latency risk (Q4).\n572\t\"\"\"\n573\t⋮----\n574\tlogger = get_logger(service=\"meterly\")\n575\t⋮----\n576\t_BEARER_PREFIX = \"Bearer \"\n577\t⋮----\n578\t@dataclass\n579\tclass _CachedVerification\n580\t⋮----\n581\t\"\"\"An in-process cache entry: the digest of the secret that was last\n582\t    verified for this `key_id`, and the resolved principal.\"\"\"\n583\t⋮----\n584\tsecret_digest: str\n585\tprincipal: AuthenticatedPrincipal\n586\tcached_at: float\n587\t⋮----\n588\tclass ApiKeyVerificationCache\n589\t⋮----\n590\t\"\"\"Per-process cache mapping a token's public `key_id` to its last-verified\n591\t    secret digest and resolved principal, with a TTL.\n592\t\n593\t    Keyed on the *public* `key_id` (not a secret) so the cache lookup itself\n594\t    leaks nothing; the constant-time digest comparison is what actually\n595\t    authorizes a cache hit.\n596\t    \"\"\"\n597\t⋮----\n598\tdef __init__(self, ttl_seconds: int) -> None\n599\t⋮----\n600\tdef get(self, key_id: str, secret_digest: str) -> AuthenticatedPrincipal | None\n601\t⋮----\n602\t\"\"\"Return the cached principal if `key_id` has a fresh, matching entry.\"\"\"\n603\tentry = self._entries.get(key_id)\n604\t⋮----\n605\tdef put(self, key_id: str, secret_digest: str, principal: AuthenticatedPrincipal) -> None\n606\t⋮----\n607\t\"\"\"Cache a freshly Argon2id-verified principal for `key_id`.\"\"\"\n608\t⋮----\n609\tdef invalidate(self, key_id: str) -> None\n610\t⋮----\n611\t\"\"\"Drop a cached entry (used by tests and any future revocation channel).\"\"\"\n612\t⋮----\n613\t_verification_cache: ApiKeyVerificationCache | None = None\n614\t⋮----\n615\tdef _get_verification_cache() -> ApiKeyVerificationCache\n616\t⋮----\n617\t\"\"\"Return the process-wide verification cache, created on first use.\"\"\"\n618\t⋮----\n619\t_verification_cache = ApiKeyVerificationCache(get_settings().api_key_cache_ttl_seconds)\n620\t⋮----\n621\tdef _extract_bearer_token(request: Request) -> str | None\n622\t⋮----\n623\t\"\"\"Pull the raw bearer token out of the `Authorization` header, if present and well-formed.\"\"\"\n624\theader_value = request.headers.get(\"authorization\")\n625\t⋮----\n626\tasync def require_api_key(request: Request) -> AuthenticatedPrincipal\n627\t⋮----\n628\t\"\"\"FastAPI dependency: authenticate the request's API key.\n629\t\n630\t    Cache hit path: constant-time digest compare only (no Argon2id). Cache\n631\t    miss: split-token parse + DB lookup + Argon2id verify, then populate the\n632\t    cache. Any failure raises 401 — malformed header, unknown/revoked key, and\n633\t    a wrong secret are all indistinguishable to the caller.\n634\t    \"\"\"\n635\tpresented_key = _extract_bearer_token(request)\n636\t⋮----\n637\tparsed = parse_split_token(presented_key)\n638\t⋮----\n639\tsecret_digest = sha256_digest(presented_key)\n640\tcache = _get_verification_cache()\n641\tcached_principal = cache.get(parsed.key_id, secret_digest)\n642\t⋮----\n643\tprincipal = await verify_api_key(connection, presented_key)\n644\t⋮----\n645\tApiKeyPrincipal = Depends(require_api_key)\n646\t</file>\n647\t\n648\t<file path=\"src/auth/rate_limit.py\">\n649\t\"\"\"Redis-backed token-bucket rate limiting — Tier 1 (pre-auth, IP+route) and\n650\tTier 2 (post-auth, per-`api_key_id`).\n651\t\n652\tState lives in Redis, never in-process: an in-process counter is per-task and\n653\tfails open behind the ALB once there is more than one Fargate task\n654\t(`api-edge-conventions`). The bucket check-and-decrement is a single atomic\n655\tLua script so concurrent requests against the same bucket can't race past the\n656\tlimit (the same TOCTOU concern the events idempotency mechanism addresses,\n657\tapplied to a counter instead of a unique constraint).\n658\t\"\"\"\n659\t⋮----\n660\t# Atomic token-bucket refill + consume: KEYS[1] = bucket key.\n661\t# ARGV: capacity, refill_rate_per_second, now_ms, cost.\n662\t# Returns {allowed (0/1), tokens_remaining, retry_after_ms}.\n663\t_TOKEN_BUCKET_LUA = \"\"\"\n664\t⋮----\n665\t@dataclass(frozen=True)\n666\tclass RateLimitDecision\n667\t⋮----\n668\t\"\"\"The outcome of a rate-limit check: whether the request is allowed and,\n669\t    if not, how long the caller should wait before retrying.\"\"\"\n670\t⋮----\n671\tallowed: bool\n672\tretry_after_seconds: float\n673\t⋮----\n674\tclass RedisTokenBucketLimiter\n675\t⋮----\n676\t\"\"\"A shared, atomic Redis token-bucket limiter used by both throttle tiers.\n677\t\n678\t    Each tier instantiates this with its own key prefix and capacity/refill\n679\t    policy; the Lua script guarantees the check-then-decrement is race-free\n680\t    across concurrently arriving requests and across Fargate tasks.\n681\t    \"\"\"\n682\t⋮----\n683\tdef __init__(self, redis_client: redis.Redis, *, key_prefix: str) -> None\n684\t⋮----\n685\t\"\"\"Consume `cost` tokens from `bucket_identity`'s bucket; returns the decision.\"\"\"\n686\t⋮----\n687\tnow_ms = int(time.time() * 1000)\n688\t⋮----\n689\t_redis_client: redis.Redis | None = None\n690\t_tier1_limiter: RedisTokenBucketLimiter | None = None\n691\t_tier2_limiter: RedisTokenBucketLimiter | None = None\n692\t⋮----\n693\tdef get_redis_client() -> redis.Redis\n694\t⋮----\n695\t\"\"\"Return the process-wide async Redis client, creating it on first use\n696\t    (deferred, like the DB engine, so import stays dependency-free).\"\"\"\n697\t⋮----\n698\t_redis_client = redis.from_url(get_settings().redis_url, decode_responses=True)\n699\t⋮----\n700\tdef get_tier1_limiter() -> RedisTokenBucketLimiter\n701\t⋮----\n702\t\"\"\"Return the Tier-1 (pre-auth, IP+route-keyed) limiter singleton.\"\"\"\n703\t⋮----\n704\t_tier1_limiter = RedisTokenBucketLimiter(get_redis_client(), key_prefix=\"ratelimit:tier1\")\n705\t⋮----\n706\tdef get_tier2_limiter() -> RedisTokenBucketLimiter\n707\t⋮----\n708\t\"\"\"Return the Tier-2 (post-auth, `api_key_id`-keyed) limiter singleton.\"\"\"\n709\t⋮----\n710\t_tier2_limiter = RedisTokenBucketLimiter(get_redis_client(), key_prefix=\"ratelimit:tier2\")\n711\t⋮----\n712\tasync def dispose_redis_client() -> None\n713\t⋮----\n714\t\"\"\"Close the Redis client (called from lifespan shutdown).\"\"\"\n715\t⋮----\n716\t_redis_client = None\n717\t_tier1_limiter = None\n718\t_tier2_limiter = None\n719\t⋮----\n720\tasync def enforce_tier2_rate_limit(request: \"Request\", principal: \"AuthenticatedPrincipal\") -> None\n721\t⋮----\n722\t\"\"\"Tier-2 dependency: enforce the caller's per-`api_key_id` token bucket.\n723\t\n724\t    Registered on a dependency that runs strictly **after** `require_api_key`\n725\t    (both endpoint routes depend on this ordering), so the bucket key is\n726\t    always the authenticated principal, never the client IP — this is the\n727\t    property the two-principals-one-IP test verifies (AC14/AC16).\n728\t\n729\t    Fails **open** (logs a warning, allows the request) on a Redis connection\n730\t    error — a cache outage degrading every authenticated call to \"temporarily\n731\t    unlimited\" is preferable to a full ingest outage; the durable UNIQUE-\n732\t    constraint/transaction guarantees are unaffected either way.\n733\t    \"\"\"\n734\t⋮----\n735\tdecision = await get_tier2_limiter().check(\n736\texcept Exception:  # noqa: BLE001 - a Redis outage must not take down the whole API\n737\t</file>\n738\t\n739\t<file path=\"src/config/__init__.py\">\n740\t\"\"\"Configuration and secrets facades.\"\"\"\n741\t</file>\n742\t\n743\t<file path=\"src/config/README.md\">\n744\t# src/config/\n745\t\n746\t## Purpose\n747\t\n748\tApplication configuration and secrets management: environment variables, dependency injection, and AWS Secrets Manager integration for database credentials.\n749\t\n750\t## Modules\n751\t\n752\t| File / Module | Responsibility |\n753\t|---|---|\n754\t| `settings.py` | `Settings` — Pydantic BaseSettings config class; loads all environment variables at app startup. Singleton instance available as `settings`. |\n755\t| `secrets.py` | `fetch_db_credentials()` — fetches the RDS database connection string from AWS Secrets Manager (if `DATABASE_URL` is not already set). Async function, called during lifespan startup. |\n756\t\n757\t## Relationships\n758\t\n759\t**Public surface:**\n760\t- `settings` (module-level singleton) is imported by many modules: `src/auth`, `src/logging`, `src/observability`, `src/db`, `src/main.py`.\n761\t- `fetch_db_credentials()` is called once at app startup in `src/main.py` (lifespan context manager).\n762\t\n763\t**Dependencies:**\n764\t- `settings.py` uses Pydantic v2 for validation and type-checking.\n765\t- `secrets.py` imports boto3 (AWS SDK) to call `SecretsManager.get_secret_value()`.\n766\t\n767\t**Configuration sources:**\n768\t- Environment variables are the primary source (12-factor app pattern).\n769\t- If `DATABASE_URL` is not set, `fetch_db_credentials()` fetches it from Secrets Manager.\n770\t- Required env vars: `DATABASE_URL` (or AWS credentials + secret name), `REDIS_URL`, `RELEASE_SHA`.\n771\t- Optional: `SENTRY_DSN`, `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT`, `LOG_LEVEL`, `ENVIRONMENT`.\n772\t\n773\t## Notes\n774\t\n775\t**Settings attributes:**\n776\t- `database_url` — async PostgreSQL connection string (e.g., `postgresql+asyncpg://user:pass@host/dbname`).\n777\t- `redis_url` — Redis connection string (e.g., `redis://host:6379/0`).\n778\t- `release_sha` — commit hash (for Sentry and X-Ray tagging).\n779\t- `sentry_dsn` — Sentry project DSN (optional; if unset, Sentry is disabled).\n780\t- `otel_exporter_otlp_endpoint` — OTel exporter endpoint (optional; if unset, OTel is disabled).\n781\t- `log_level` — structlog verbosity (default: INFO).\n782\t- `environment` — deployment context (local/staging/prod).\n783\t\n784\t**Secrets Manager integration:**\n785\t- At startup, if `DATABASE_URL` is not set, `fetch_db_credentials()` is called.\n786\t- It retrieves the secret named in the `DB_SECRET_NAME` env var (default: `meterly/rds/credentials`).\n787\t- The secret is expected to be a JSON object with keys: `username`, `password`, `host`, `port`, `dbname`.\n788\t- The function constructs the async connection string: `postgresql+asyncpg://user:pass@host:port/dbname`.\n789\t\n790\t**Validation:**\n791\t- Pydantic validates all env vars at load time.\n792\t- Missing required fields raise a `ValidationError` at startup (fail-fast).\n793\t- Type mismatches (e.g., non-integer PORT) are caught immediately.\n794\t\n795\t**Testing:**\n796\t- Local dev uses the `smoke.env` file (checked into the repo) with defaults (no secrets).\n797\t- CI uses environment variables set by the test runner or GitHub Actions secrets.\n798\t- Prod uses AWS Secrets Manager for the database credential (IAM-authenticated fetch).\n799\t</file>\n800\t\n801\t<file path=\"src/config/secrets.py\">\n802\t\"\"\"Runtime secrets facade — the only module that talks to AWS Secrets Manager / SSM.\n803\t\n804\tBusiness logic never calls `boto3` or reads a secret value from `os.environ`\n805\tdirectly (`secrets-management`). Bootstrap env vars only locate *which* secret\n806\tto fetch (see `Settings`); the value itself is retrieved here, cached briefly\n807\tin-process, and re-fetched on TTL expiry so rotation is picked up without a\n808\tredeploy.\n809\t\"\"\"\n810\t⋮----\n811\t_CACHE_TTL_SECONDS = 600\n812\t⋮----\n813\t@dataclass\n814\tclass _CachedSecret\n815\t⋮----\n816\t\"\"\"A secret value cached in-process with the time it was fetched.\"\"\"\n817\t⋮----\n818\tvalue: str\n819\tfetched_at: float\n820\t⋮----\n821\tclass SecretsFacade\n822\t⋮----\n823\t\"\"\"Fetches and caches runtime secrets from AWS Secrets Manager, with an\n824\t    environment-variable fallback for local development.\n825\t\n826\t    Never call `boto3` directly from anywhere else in the codebase — route\n827\t    every secret read through `get_secret()` so caching, fallback, and\n828\t    redaction stay centralized.\n829\t    \"\"\"\n830\t⋮----\n831\tdef __init__(self) -> None\n832\t⋮----\n833\tdef _client_or_create(self) -> Any\n834\t⋮----\n835\t\"\"\"Lazily create the Secrets Manager client (avoids a network call at import time).\"\"\"\n836\t⋮----\n837\tdef get_secret(self, secret_name: str, *, env_fallback: str | None = None) -> str\n838\t⋮----\n839\t\"\"\"Return the current value of `secret_name`, fetching from Secrets\n840\t        Manager (with a short-TTL in-process cache) or `env_fallback` for local\n841\t        development.\n842\t\n843\t        Raises `RuntimeError` if the secret cannot be resolved anywhere — this\n844\t        facade never falls back to a hardcoded default.\n845\t        \"\"\"\n846\tcached = self._cache.get(secret_name)\n847\t⋮----\n848\tvalue = self._fetch_from_manager(secret_name)\n849\t⋮----\n850\tvalue = os.environ.get(env_fallback)\n851\t⋮----\n852\tdef _fetch_from_manager(self, secret_name: str) -> str | None\n853\t⋮----\n854\t\"\"\"Attempt a live Secrets Manager lookup; returns None on any failure\n855\t        so local/dev environments without AWS credentials can fall back.\"\"\"\n856\t⋮----\n857\tresponse = self._client_or_create().get_secret_value(SecretId=secret_name)\n858\texcept (ClientError, Exception):  # noqa: BLE001 - any AWS/credential failure falls through\n859\t⋮----\n860\t_facade = SecretsFacade()\n861\t⋮----\n862\tdef get_secret(secret_name: str, *, env_fallback: str | None = None) -> str\n863\t⋮----\n864\t\"\"\"Module-level convenience wrapper around the process-wide `SecretsFacade`.\"\"\"\n865\t⋮----\n866\tdef get_database_url() -> str\n867\t⋮----\n868\t\"\"\"Return the database connection string via the secrets facade.\"\"\"\n869\tsettings = get_settings()\n870\t</file>\n871\t\n872\t<file path=\"src/config/settings.py\">\n873\t\"\"\"Configuration facade — the single place application code reads bootstrap config.\n874\t\n875\tOnly *non-secret* bootstrap values live here (region, resource names/ARNs, feature\n876\tflags). Secret values are never read directly from the environment in business\n877\tlogic — see `src/config/secrets.py`, which fetches them at runtime through AWS\n878\tSecrets Manager / SSM behind its own facade.\n879\t\"\"\"\n880\t⋮----\n881\tclass Settings(BaseSettings)\n882\t⋮----\n883\t\"\"\"Process-wide bootstrap configuration, populated from environment variables.\n884\t\n885\t    Every field here is safe to log or inspect — it locates secrets, it never\n886\t    holds one. Actual secret *values* (DB password, API-key pepper, etc.) come\n887\t    from `src.config.secrets.get_secret()`.\n888\t    \"\"\"\n889\t⋮----\n890\tmodel_config = SettingsConfigDict(env_prefix=\"METERLY_\", extra=\"ignore\")\n891\t⋮----\n892\tenvironment: str = \"local\"\n893\tservice_name: str = \"meterly\"\n894\taws_region: str = \"us-east-1\"\n895\t⋮----\n896\t# Bootstrap pointers to secrets — names/ARNs only, never the secret value.\n897\tdatabase_secret_name: str = \"meterly/database-url\"\n898\tdatabase_secret_env_fallback: str = \"DATABASE_URL\"\n899\t⋮----\n900\t# Redis connection is treated as config, not secret (no credential embedded\n901\t# when using the in-VPC ElastiCache endpoint with IAM/network-level auth).\n902\tredis_url: str = \"redis://localhost:6379/0\"\n903\t⋮----\n904\t# Rate limiting defaults (per-key override lives in api_keys.rate_limit_per_sec).\n905\ttier1_rate_limit_per_second: int = 200\n906\ttier1_rate_limit_burst: int = 400\n907\t⋮----\n908\t# Edge behavior.\n909\tmax_body_size_bytes: int = 8 * 1024  # 8 KiB — see api-edge-conventions body guard\n910\tcors_allowed_origins: tuple[str, ...] = ()  # server-to-server API: empty by default\n911\t⋮----\n912\t# Auth verification cache TTL (seconds) — see src/auth/__init__.py.\n913\tapi_key_cache_ttl_seconds: int = 300\n914\t⋮----\n915\t# Observability.\n916\tsentry_dsn: str | None = None\n917\totel_exporter_otlp_endpoint: str | None = None\n918\trelease_sha: str = \"local-dev\"\n919\t⋮----\n920\t# Docs/OpenAPI exposure (disabled in prod per ASVS 13.4.5).\n921\tenable_docs: bool = True\n922\t⋮----\n923\t@lru_cache\n924\tdef get_settings() -> Settings\n925\t⋮----\n926\t\"\"\"Return the process-wide `Settings` singleton (cached — env is read once).\"\"\"\n927\t</file>\n928\t\n929\t<file path=\"src/crypto/__init__.py\">\n930\t\"\"\"DataProtection crypto facade — the only module allowed to touch a KDF or a\n931\tconstant-time comparison.\n932\t\n933\tEvery field that needs a credential-class at-rest control (`api_keys.secret_hash`)\n934\troutes through here rather than calling `argon2-cffi` inline. Centralizing this\n935\tkeeps the mechanism greppable and auditable in one place (`data-protection-conventions`).\n936\t\"\"\"\n937\t⋮----\n938\t# Argon2id is deliberately slow (tens of ms) — this is the load-bearing property\n939\t# that makes brute-forcing a stolen hash expensive. See src/auth/__init__.py for\n940\t# how the request path avoids paying this cost on every request via a verification\n941\t# cache, while the at-rest store stays Argon2id-only (never a faster hash).\n942\t_password_hasher = PasswordHasher()\n943\t⋮----\n944\tdef hash_secret(secret: str) -> str\n945\t⋮----\n946\t\"\"\"Hash an API-key secret with Argon2id for storage (`api_keys.secret_hash`).\n947\t\n948\t    Returns the encoded Argon2id hash string (includes algorithm parameters and\n949\t    salt) — never the plaintext secret.\n950\t    \"\"\"\n951\t⋮----\n952\tdef verify_secret(secret: str, stored_hash: str) -> bool\n953\t⋮----\n954\t\"\"\"Verify a presented secret against its stored Argon2id hash.\n955\t\n956\t    Returns True on match, False on any mismatch/malformed-hash error — never\n957\t    raises to the caller so a bad stored value can't become a 500 that leaks\n958\t    detail.\n959\t    \"\"\"\n960\t⋮----\n961\texcept Exception:  # noqa: BLE001 - a malformed/legacy hash must fail closed, not 500\n962\t⋮----\n963\tdef sha256_digest(value: str) -> str\n964\t⋮----\n965\t\"\"\"Return the hex SHA-256 digest of `value`.\n966\t\n967\t    Used to key the in-process API-key verification cache: the cache stores a\n968\t    digest of a high-entropy 128-bit secret, never the secret itself, and a\n969\t    digest can't be reversed to recover the key (`src/auth/__init__.py`).\n970\t    \"\"\"\n971\t⋮----\n972\tdef constant_time_equals(left: str, right: str) -> bool\n973\t⋮----\n974\t\"\"\"Compare two strings in constant time to avoid a timing side-channel.\n975\t\n976\t    Used for the verification-cache digest comparison (ASVS 11.2.4 — in-scope\n977\t    L3 for this project because usage data is billing-grade).\n978\t    \"\"\"\n979\t</file>\n980\t\n981\t<file path=\"src/crypto/README.md\">\n982\t# src/crypto/\n983\t\n984\t## Purpose\n985\t\n986\tCryptographic utilities: Argon2id credential hashing (for API key secrets), constant-time comparison, and credential generation.\n987\t\n988\t## Modules\n989\t\n990\t| File / Module | Responsibility |\n991\t|---|---|\n992\t| `__init__.py` | `hash_secret(secret: str) -> str` — Argon2id hash; `verify_secret(secret: str, hash: str) -> bool` — constant-time comparison; `generate_secret(length: int) -> str` — random secret generation. |\n993\t\n994\t## Relationships\n995\t\n996\t**Public surface:**\n997\t- `hash_secret()` is called by `scripts/seed_api_key.py` when provisioning a new API key.\n998\t- `verify_secret()` is called by `src/auth.api_key` during credential verification (cache miss or always-verify path).\n999\t- `generate_secret()` is called by the key provisioning script.\n1000\t\n1001\t**Dependencies:**\n1002\t- Imports `argon2` library (from `argon2-cffi` package, a native binding to libargon2).\n1003\t- Imports `secrets` module (Python standard library) for random generation.\n1004\t\n1005\t**Usage context:**\n1006\t- At API key creation, the plaintext secret is hashed with Argon2id and stored as `api_keys.secret_hash`.\n1007\t- The plaintext secret is returned to the caller (displayed once, never stored).\n1008\t- At authentication (every request), the provided secret is verified against the stored hash using constant-time comparison (prevents timing attacks).\n1009\t\n1010\t## Notes\n1011\t\n1012\t**Argon2id parameters:**\n1013\t- Memory: 65 MiB (reasonable for container workloads; balances security and latency).\n1014\t- Time cost: 3 iterations (calibrated to ~100ms on typical hardware).\n1015\t- Parallelism: 4 threads.\n1016\t- These parameters are frozen in code (not configurable); they match industry defaults and the OWASP recommendation.\n1017\t\n1018\t**Constant-time comparison (TIMING-ATTACK-RESISTANT):**\n1019\t- The `verify_secret()` function uses `argon2.PasswordHasher.verify()`, which internally uses `hmac.compare_digest()`.\n1020\t- This ensures the comparison time is independent of the input (no early-exit on first mismatch).\n1021\t- Protects against timing side-channel attacks (attacker timing the response to infer secret bytes).\n1022\t\n1023\t**Credential generation:**\n1024\t- `generate_secret()` uses `secrets.token_urlsafe(length)` to generate a URL-safe random string.\n1025\t- Default length: 32 bytes, encoded as 43 characters (base64url).\n1026\t- Output is suitable for use as the secret half of a split-token API key.\n1027\t\n1028\t**Test coverage:**\n1029\t- `tests/test_crypto.py` verifies:\n1030\t  - Hash format is Argon2id (starts with `$argon2id$...`).\n1031\t  - Plaintext secret is never stored or logged.\n1032\t  - Correct secret verifies (returns True).\n1033\t  - Incorrect secret is rejected (returns False).\n1034\t  - Hash is salted and unique (two hashes of the same secret are different).\n1035\t</file>\n1036\t\n1037\t<file path=\"src/db/__init__.py\">\n1038\t\"\"\"Database engine/session management.\"\"\"\n1039\t</file>\n1040\t\n1041\t<file path=\"src/logging/__init__.py\">\n1042\t\"\"\"Structured logging facade — `get_logger()` is the only way application code\n1043\tshould obtain a logger.\n1044\t\n1045\tConfigures structlog once at import time to emit JSON to stdout (ECS ships\n1046\tstdout to CloudWatch with no further app change) and applies a centralized\n1047\tredaction processor so a secret or raw PII value can never leave the process\n1048\tthrough a log line, regardless of which call site logs it.\n1049\t\"\"\"\n1050\t⋮----\n1051\t_REDACTED = \"***redacted***\"\n1052\t⋮----\n1053\t# Field names that must never appear in raw form in a log event — the API-key\n1054\t# secret/Authorization header and any raw customer identifier (personal data\n1055\t# class per data-protection-conventions). Matched case-insensitively against\n1056\t# structlog event-dict keys.\n1057\t_SENSITIVE_KEYS = frozenset(\n1058\t⋮----\n1059\t\"\"\"Strip sensitive values from a structlog event dict before it is rendered.\n1060\t\n1061\t    This is the centralized PII/secret-redaction control every log call\n1062\t    inherits automatically — call sites never redact ad hoc.\n1063\t    \"\"\"\n1064\t⋮----\n1065\t\"\"\"Neutralize newlines/control characters in string values to prevent log forging.\"\"\"\n1066\t⋮----\n1067\tdef _configure_structlog() -> None\n1068\t⋮----\n1069\t\"\"\"Configure structlog once at import time: JSON renderer, ISO timestamps,\n1070\t    the redaction/anti-forging processors, and stdlib logging routed through it.\"\"\"\n1071\t⋮----\n1072\tdef get_logger(**initial_values: Any) -> structlog.stdlib.BoundLogger\n1073\t⋮----\n1074\t\"\"\"Return the single configured structlog logger, optionally bound with\n1075\t    initial context values (e.g. `service=...`).\n1076\t\n1077\t    Every module imports this rather than instantiating its own logger, so\n1078\t    redaction and field conventions stay centralized (`code-standards` facade\n1079\t    rule).\n1080\t    \"\"\"\n1081\t</file>\n1082\t\n1083\t<file path=\"src/logging/middleware.py\">\n1084\t\"\"\"Request-scoped logging middleware: assigns `requestId`/`traceId`, binds them\n1085\tinto structlog's contextvars so every log line emitted during the request\n1086\tcarries them, and logs one completion event with `duration`/`statusCode`.\n1087\t\n1088\tRegistered first in the middleware stack (`src/api/middleware.py`) — outermost —\n1089\tso every mitigation below it (security headers, throttles, auth, the handler)\n1090\tlogs with a correlation id already attached.\n1091\t\"\"\"\n1092\t⋮----\n1093\tlogger = get_logger(service=\"meterly\")\n1094\t⋮----\n1095\t_AWS_TRACE_HEADER = \"x-amzn-trace-id\"\n1096\t⋮----\n1097\tdef _resolve_trace_id(request: Request) -> str\n1098\t⋮----\n1099\t\"\"\"Resolve a trace id in priority order: active OTel span, then the AWS\n1100\t    `X-Amzn-Trace-Id` header, then a freshly generated UUID.\"\"\"\n1101\tspan = trace.get_current_span()\n1102\tspan_context = span.get_span_context()\n1103\t⋮----\n1104\taws_header = request.headers.get(_AWS_TRACE_HEADER)\n1105\t⋮----\n1106\tclass RequestContextMiddleware(BaseHTTPMiddleware)\n1107\t⋮----\n1108\t\"\"\"Binds `requestId`/`traceId` to the logging context for the lifetime of\n1109\t    a request and emits one structured completion log per request.\"\"\"\n1110\t⋮----\n1111\t\"\"\"Assign correlation ids, run the request, and log its outcome.\"\"\"\n1112\trequest_id = str(uuid.uuid4())\n1113\ttrace_id = _resolve_trace_id(request)\n1114\tstarted_at = time.monotonic()\n1115\t⋮----\n1116\tresponse = await call_next(request)\n1117\t⋮----\n1118\tduration_ms = round((time.monotonic() - started_at) * 1000, 2)\n1119\t</file>\n1120\t\n1121\t<file path=\"src/logging/README.md\">\n1122\t# src/logging/\n1123\t\n1124\t## Purpose\n1125\t\n1126\tCentralized structured logging facade using structlog: request middleware (correlation context), PII redaction processor, and a uniform `get_logger()` entry point for all modules.\n1127\t\n1128\t## Modules\n1129\t\n1130\t| File / Module | Responsibility |\n1131\t|---|---|\n1132\t| `__init__.py` | `get_logger(service=...)` — returns a logger instance with the given service name; applies PII redaction. Facade entry point for all logging calls. |\n1133\t| `middleware.py` | Request middleware: extracts/generates request ID and trace ID (from OTel span or AWS X-Amzn-Trace-Id header), stores in request state for correlation. |\n1134\t\n1135\t## Relationships\n1136\t\n1137\t**Public surface:**\n1138\t- `get_logger` is imported by every module that logs: `src/api`, `src/auth`, `src/services`, `src/observability`, etc.\n1139\t- `middleware.py` is registered in `src/main.py` as part of the FastAPI middleware stack.\n1140\t\n1141\t**Dependencies:**\n1142\t- Imports `src.config.settings` for `LOG_LEVEL` environment variable.\n1143\t- Imports `structlog` for structured logging and the PII redaction pipeline.\n1144\t\n1145\t**PII redaction:**\n1146\t- The `get_logger` facade applies a redaction processor that scrubs known PII fields from log output.\n1147\t- Fields redacted: `customer_id`, `api_key_id`, `secret`, `key_id`, `idempotency_key`, and other credential-adjacent data.\n1148\t- Redacted values are replaced with a placeholder (e.g., `\"<redacted>\"` or a hash).\n1149\t- Tested in `tests/test_logging_redaction.py`: ensures no raw `customer_id` appears in any log output.\n1150\t\n1151\t**Request correlation:**\n1152\t- Request ID (unique per request) and trace ID (from OTel span context or HTTP header) are extracted by the middleware.\n1153\t- Both are stored in request state (`request.state.request_id`, `request.state.trace_id`).\n1154\t- All subsequent log calls include these in the structured context (via `structlog.contextvars`), so every log line is tagged with the request.\n1155\t- Used for tracing and debugging multi-step request flows (e.g., cache miss → DB lookup → Argon2id verify).\n1156\t\n1157\t**Log output format:**\n1158\t- JSON lines (one JSON object per log line) to stdout.\n1159\t- Consumed by the container runtime and shipped to CloudWatch.\n1160\t- Includes timestamp, log level, service name, message, context fields, request ID, trace ID.\n1161\t\n1162\t## Notes\n1163\t\n1164\t**Thread-safe and async-safe:**\n1165\t- structlog uses `contextvars` (not thread-local storage) for context propagation.\n1166\t- Safe for both sync and async code (e.g., can be called from middleware, async handlers, background tasks).\n1167\t\n1168\t**Environment variable:**\n1169\t- `LOG_LEVEL` — structlog verbosity (default: INFO). Set to DEBUG for more verbose output during development.\n1170\t\n1171\t**Custom fields:**\n1172\t- Loggers can be created with a service name: `get_logger(service=\"meterly\")`.\n1173\t- Additional context can be passed per log call: `logger.info(\"event\", key1=value1, key2=value2)`.\n1174\t- All context is included in the JSON output for structured querying (CloudWatch Logs Insights, etc.).\n1175\t</file>\n1176\t\n1177\t<file path=\"src/observability/__init__.py\">\n1178\t\"\"\"Operational observability wiring: OpenTelemetry (traces/metrics) and Sentry (errors).\"\"\"\n1179\t</file>\n1180\t\n1181\t<file path=\"src/observability/otel.py\">\n1182\t\"\"\"OpenTelemetry wiring — traces/metrics exported to the ADOT collector\n1183\tsidecar, which forwards to X-Ray (traces) and CloudWatch (metrics).\n1184\t\n1185\tConfigured once from the lifespan startup hook (`src/main.py`), never at\n1186\timport time, so `import src.main` stays dependency-free for the smoke check.\n1187\t\"\"\"\n1188\t⋮----\n1189\tdef configure_otel(app: FastAPI, settings: Settings) -> None\n1190\t⋮----\n1191\t\"\"\"Set up the OTel tracer provider and instrument the FastAPI app.\n1192\t\n1193\t    A no-op (in-memory only, no exporter) when `otel_exporter_otlp_endpoint`\n1194\t    is unset, so local/dev/smoke runs never require a reachable collector.\n1195\t    \"\"\"\n1196\tresource = Resource.create({SERVICE_NAME: settings.service_name})\n1197\tprovider = TracerProvider(resource=resource)\n1198\t⋮----\n1199\texporter = OTLPSpanExporter(endpoint=settings.otel_exporter_otlp_endpoint)\n1200\t</file>\n1201\t\n1202\t<file path=\"src/observability/README.md\">"}]},"uuid":"5b6fcaf8-c83e-43b8-b593-dfed1e9632ec","timestamp":"2026-07-09T17:30:39.505Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"1d5b7cca-f312-4f71-95d7-42355e9c3e91","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/usage-export"}
