{"parentUuid":"f9f15c14-4fbb-4fe4-a0f7-946d1784136d","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"aab619a6f776136ee","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011Ccrt4BZRG7BGhohcp3qFx","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"No prior `plan-audit.md`, so this is a first (non-revision) run. PROJECT.md and requirements both confirm no design source for this feature (it's a CSV endpoint, no UI). Let me read the rest of the pack — the usage repo/service, errors, middleware, and remaining files are the core of this feature."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":22230,"cache_read_input_tokens":28753,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":22230,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011Ccrt49CHSaWUdSvFjHsvp","attributionAgent":"planning","attributionSkill":"pipeline-orchestration","type":"assistant","uuid":"963db257-b9f3-4868-9523-65e7e82f0aa2","timestamp":"2026-07-09T17:30:46.209Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/usage-export"}
{"parentUuid":"963db257-b9f3-4868-9523-65e7e82f0aa2","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"aab619a6f776136ee","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011Ccrt4BZRG7BGhohcp3qFx","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01KXeRD2ajVih5JTSygcAcAx","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test\\.pipeline\\repomix-pack.xml","offset":1203,"limit":1227},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":22230,"cache_read_input_tokens":28753,"output_tokens":489,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":22230},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":489,"cache_read_input_tokens":28753,"cache_creation_input_tokens":22230,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":22230,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011Ccrt49CHSaWUdSvFjHsvp","attributionAgent":"planning","attributionSkill":"pipeline-orchestration","type":"assistant","uuid":"dfab60a4-dec4-4a42-9a3a-1694384c1863","timestamp":"2026-07-09T17:30:47.317Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/usage-export"}
{"parentUuid":"dfab60a4-dec4-4a42-9a3a-1694384c1863","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"53f5148a-6791-4be6-a2fc-f4eaf65be586","agentId":"aab619a6f776136ee","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01KXeRD2ajVih5JTSygcAcAx","type":"tool_result","content":"1203\t# src/observability/\n1204\t\n1205\t## Purpose\n1206\t\n1207\tObservability instrumentation: OpenTelemetry trace export (to X-Ray via ADOT sidecar), Sentry error tracking with release tagging and PII scrubbing.\n1208\t\n1209\t## Modules\n1210\t\n1211\t| File / Module | Responsibility |\n1212\t|---|---|\n1213\t| `otel.py` | OpenTelemetry initialization: sets up OTLP exporter (to ADOT sidecar), configures trace processors, tags spans with `deployment.environment` and `service.version`. |\n1214\t| `sentry.py` | Sentry initialization: sets up the SDK with release tagging, configures a `before_send` hook to scrub PII/secrets from error payloads before shipping. |\n1215\t\n1216\t## Relationships\n1217\t\n1218\t**Public surface:**\n1219\t- Both modules are initialized at app startup in `src/main.py` (lifespan context manager).\n1220\t- `configure_otel()` and `configure_sentry()` are called once during app construction.\n1221\t- No public entry points; configuration happens at the module level.\n1222\t\n1223\t**Dependencies:**\n1224\t- `otel.py` imports OpenTelemetry SDK and the OTLP exporter.\n1225\t- `sentry.py` imports the Sentry SDK.\n1226\t- Both import `src.config.settings` for endpoint URLs and the release SHA.\n1227\t\n1228\t**Instrumentation:**\n1229\t- After `configure_otel()` is called, all async I/O operations (database, HTTP requests) are automatically traced by the SDK's instrumentor libraries.\n1230\t- OTel traces are exported to the ADOT sidecar (expected at `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT`, e.g., `http://localhost:4317`).\n1231\t- The sidecar forwards traces to AWS X-Ray.\n1232\t- Trace data includes span duration, status (success/error), attributes (e.g., `db.statement`, `http.status_code`).\n1233\t\n1234\t**Error reporting:**\n1235\t- Unhandled exceptions propagate to Sentry (if configured and enabled).\n1236\t- The `before_send` hook in Sentry's configuration scrubs PII fields (same redaction as structured logging: `customer_id`, `secret`, etc.).\n1237\t- Release is tagged with the commit SHA (`settings.release_sha`), so errors are tracked per deployment.\n1238\t\n1239\t## Notes\n1240\t\n1241\t**Optional configuration:**\n1242\t- If `SENTRY_DSN` is not set, Sentry is disabled (no-op initialization).\n1243\t- If `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT` is not set, OTel exports are disabled (no-op).\n1244\t- Both are non-gating: the app runs fine without them (traces and errors are just not collected).\n1245\t\n1246\t**Environment variables:**\n1247\t- `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT` — ADOT sidecar endpoint (default: `http://localhost:4317`).\n1248\t- `SENTRY_DSN` — Sentry project DSN (omit to disable).\n1249\t- `RELEASE_SHA` — commit hash for release tagging (set by container build).\n1250\t- `ENVIRONMENT` — deployment environment (prod/staging/local; used in trace/error context).\n1251\t\n1252\t**PII scrubbing (before_send):**\n1253\t- Sentry's `before_send` is registered with a custom hook that removes sensitive fields from error payloads.\n1254\t- Matches the same field list as structured logging redaction.\n1255\t- Ensures no raw `customer_id`, `secret`, or API keys leak into error tracking.\n1256\t</file>\n1257\t\n1258\t<file path=\"src/observability/sentry.py\">\n1259\t\"\"\"Sentry error tracking wiring — release-tagged to the deploy commit SHA\n1260\t(the same SHA `build-provenance` signs and `deploy.yml` rolls out).\n1261\t\n1262\tA `before_send` hook strips the API key / `Authorization` header and\n1263\t`customer_id` at the SDK boundary, so PII/secrets never leave the process\n1264\teven if an exception's context happens to carry them.\n1265\t\"\"\"\n1266\t⋮----\n1267\t_STRIPPED_KEYS = frozenset({\"authorization\", \"api_key\", \"customer_id\", \"secret\", \"secret_hash\"})\n1268\t⋮----\n1269\tdef _strip_sensitive_context(event: dict[str, Any], _hint: dict[str, Any]) -> dict[str, Any]\n1270\t⋮----\n1271\t\"\"\"Redact known-sensitive keys from the outgoing Sentry event's request context.\"\"\"\n1272\trequest_context = event.get(\"request\")\n1273\t⋮----\n1274\theaders = request_context.get(\"headers\")\n1275\t⋮----\n1276\tdata = request_context.get(\"data\")\n1277\t⋮----\n1278\tdef configure_sentry(settings: Settings) -> None\n1279\t⋮----\n1280\t\"\"\"Initialize the Sentry SDK if `sentry_dsn` is configured.\n1281\t\n1282\t    A no-op when unset, so local/dev/smoke runs never require a DSN.\n1283\t    \"\"\"\n1284\t</file>\n1285\t\n1286\t<file path=\"src/README.md\">\n1287\t# src/\n1288\t\n1289\t## Purpose\n1290\t\n1291\tThe main application package for the Meterly metering engine. Contains the FastAPI application entry point, API route handlers, domain services, data repositories, and supporting infrastructure (auth, logging, observability, database, configuration).\n1292\t\n1293\t## Modules\n1294\t\n1295\t| Directory / Module | Responsibility |\n1296\t|---|---|\n1297\t| `main.py` | FastAPI application factory; middleware registration; lifespan startup/shutdown (DB pool, Redis, OTel/Sentry init). |\n1298\t| `api/` | HTTP API layer: routes, schemas, error handlers, middleware (request ID, security headers, CORS). Public surface for all incoming HTTP requests. |\n1299\t| `services/` | Business logic layer: event ingestion, usage aggregation, time-window calculations. Orchestrates repositories and enforces invariants (idempotency, counter atomicity). |\n1300\t| `repositories/` | Data access layer: SQL queries wrapped with parameterization, RLS scoping, and minimal-field projections. All database I/O is here. |\n1301\t| `auth/` | Authentication and authorization: API key verification (split-token, Argon2id verify cache), Tier-1 and Tier-2 rate limiting (Redis token buckets). |\n1302\t| `logging/` | Structured logging facade (structlog): request middleware, PII redaction, observability correlation. |\n1303\t| `observability/` | OTel and Sentry integration: trace/span management, release tagging, error scrubbing. |\n1304\t| `config/` | Configuration and secrets management: environment variables, dependency injection, Secrets Manager fetch. |\n1305\t| `db/` | Database connectivity: async SQLAlchemy session factory, RLS scoping, connection pooling. |\n1306\t| `crypto/` | Cryptographic utilities: Argon2id hashing, constant-time comparison, credential generation. |\n1307\t\n1308\t## Relationships\n1309\t\n1310\t**Layered architecture:**\n1311\t- **Request flow (inbound):** HTTP request → `main.py` (middleware stack) → `api/` routes → `auth/` guards (rate limit, API key verify) → request handler → `services/` business logic → `repositories/` SQL → database.\n1312\t- **Response flow (outbound):** Database result → `repositories/` minimal projection → `services/` aggregate/format → `api/` routes → `api/errors.py` error envelope → HTTP response (via middleware: add correlation/security headers).\n1313\t\n1314\t**Public surfaces (facades):**\n1315\t- `api.routes` — HTTP handlers; imported by `main.py` to register with FastAPI. Entry point for all external callers.\n1316\t- `auth` — `require_api_key` guard; imported by routes to gate handler execution. Enforces two rate-limit tiers.\n1317\t- `logging.get_logger` — centralized structured logging facade with PII redaction. Imported by every module that logs.\n1318\t- `config.settings` — environment configuration singleton; imported at startup and by modules needing env values.\n1319\t- `db.session_context` — async session factory for transactional scope. Imported by services and repositories.\n1320\t\n1321\t**Dependencies (inbound imports):**\n1322\t- `repositories` are imported only by `services` (single-responsibility: services orchestrate the data layer).\n1323\t- `services` are imported only by `api.routes` (single-responsibility: routes dispatch to business logic).\n1324\t- `auth` is imported by `main.py` (to register guards) and by `api.routes` (to call the guard).\n1325\t- `logging`, `config`, `db` are imported by multiple modules as cross-cutting infrastructure.\n1326\t\n1327\t## Notes\n1328\t\n1329\t**Environment variables** consumed by `config/settings.py`:\n1330\t- `DATABASE_URL` — PostgreSQL connection string (async, with app-role credentials).\n1331\t- `REDIS_URL` — ElastiCache Redis URL for rate limiting.\n1332\t- `SENTRY_DSN` — Sentry error-tracking endpoint (omit to disable; non-gating).\n1333\t- `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT` — OTel collector endpoint (ADOT sidecar in prod; omit to disable).\n1334\t- `LOG_LEVEL` — structlog verbosity (default: INFO).\n1335\t- `RELEASE_SHA` — commit SHA (set by the container build; used for Sentry/X-Ray tagging).\n1336\t\n1337\t**Deployment contract:**\n1338\t- The container entrypoint runs `uvicorn src.main:app` (see `Dockerfile`).\n1339\t- At startup (`lifespan`), all async resources are initialized (DB, Redis, OTel, Sentry).\n1340\t- At shutdown (SIGTERM), resources drain gracefully (connection close, request drain, cleanup).\n1341\t- `/health` (liveness) requires no dependencies and can be called at any time.\n1342\t- `/health/ready` (readiness) requires the DB and migration head to be intact.\n1343\t</file>\n1344\t\n1345\t<file path=\"src/repositories/__init__.py\">\n1346\t\"\"\"Repositories — bound-parameter SQL, always scoped by the authenticated api_key_id.\"\"\"\n1347\t</file>\n1348\t\n1349\t<file path=\"src/repositories/events_repo.py\">\n1350\t\"\"\"Repository for `events` + the `usage_rollup` increment — the idempotent\n1351\tinsert-and-aggregate primitive at the core of `POST /v1/events`.\n1352\t\n1353\tEvery query here is scoped by the authenticated `api_key_id` (the row-level-\n1354\tsecurity invariant from `code-standards`); the PostgreSQL RLS policy on both\n1355\ttables is the backstop if this scoping were ever missing.\n1356\t\"\"\"\n1357\t⋮----\n1358\t@dataclass(frozen=True)\n1359\tclass EventRecord\n1360\t⋮----\n1361\t\"\"\"A row of `events`, the fields the service layer returns to the caller.\"\"\"\n1362\t⋮----\n1363\tid: int\n1364\tapi_key_id: int\n1365\tcustomer_id: str\n1366\tmetric: str\n1367\tquantity: Decimal\n1368\tidempotency_key: str\n1369\twindow_start: datetime\n1370\t⋮----\n1371\t\"\"\"Insert a new event row unless `(api_key_id, idempotency_key)` already\n1372\t    exists; returns None when the row already existed (a duplicate replay).\n1373\t\n1374\t    The `UNIQUE (api_key_id, idempotency_key)` constraint + `ON CONFLICT DO\n1375\t    NOTHING` is the sole source of truth for \"have I seen this key before?\" —\n1376\t    evaluated atomically by PostgreSQL, so 50 concurrent identical requests\n1377\t    produce exactly one winner (AC-CONCURRENCY) with no application-level lock.\n1378\t    \"\"\"\n1379\tresult = await session.execute(\n1380\trow = result.mappings().first()\n1381\t⋮----\n1382\t\"\"\"Fetch the original event for a duplicate `idempotency_key` replay.\n1383\t\n1384\t    Scoped by `api_key_id` first — an idempotency key is only ever unique\n1385\t    within its owning tenant (plan's \"idempotency_key scope\" note), so this\n1386\t    also doubles as the tenant-isolation guard for the replay read.\n1387\t    \"\"\"\n1388\t⋮----\n1389\t\"\"\"Upsert the hourly rollup counter for `(api_key_id, customer_id, metric,\n1390\t    window_start)`, adding `quantity` and incrementing `event_count` by one.\n1391\t\n1392\t    Only called after `insert_event_if_new` returns a row (this request won\n1393\t    the insert) — a duplicate replay must never reach here, which is exactly\n1394\t    why duplicates never double-count (AC2).\n1395\t    \"\"\"\n1396\t</file>\n1397\t\n1398\t<file path=\"src/repositories/quotas_repo.py\">\n1399\t\"\"\"Repository for `quotas` — the per-tenant, per-customer, per-metric usage\n1400\tcap `upsert_quota` writes, and the atomic read-and-decide\n1401\t`read_tenant_quota_state_locked` `POST /v1/events` consults.\n1402\t\n1403\tEvery query here is scoped by the authenticated `api_key_id` first (the\n1404\trow-level-security invariant from `code-standards`); the PostgreSQL RLS\n1405\tpolicy `quotas_tenant_isolation` is the backstop if this scoping were ever\n1406\tmissing from a query.\n1407\t\"\"\"\n1408\t⋮----\n1409\t@dataclass(frozen=True)\n1410\tclass QuotaRecord\n1411\t⋮----\n1412\t\"\"\"The stored/echoed shape of a `quotas` row plus whether this call\n1413\t    created it (`inserted`) or replaced an existing cap.\"\"\"\n1414\t⋮----\n1415\tcustomer_id: str\n1416\tmetric: str\n1417\tlimit_per_window: int\n1418\tinserted: bool\n1419\t⋮----\n1420\t@dataclass(frozen=True)\n1421\tclass QuotaState\n1422\t⋮----\n1423\t\"\"\"The result of the atomic read-and-decide: the configured cap and the\n1424\t    current-window rollup total, read together under `FOR UPDATE OF q`.\"\"\"\n1425\t⋮----\n1426\tcurrent_total: Decimal\n1427\t⋮----\n1428\t\"\"\"Create-or-replace the cap for `(api_key_id, customer_id, metric)` in\n1429\t    one statement, reporting whether this call inserted a new row.\n1430\t\n1431\t    `RETURNING (xmax = 0) AS inserted` is the idiom that distinguishes a\n1432\t    fresh `INSERT` from an `ON CONFLICT DO UPDATE` in a single round-trip: a\n1433\t    freshly inserted row's `xmax` (the deleting-transaction marker) is still\n1434\t    zero, while an updated row's `xmax` is set by the `UPDATE` — so the\n1435\t    service can map `inserted -> 201` else `200` without a second read-before-\n1436\t    write query or the TOCTOU race that would introduce.\n1437\t    \"\"\"\n1438\tresult = await session.execute(\n1439\trow = result.mappings().one()\n1440\t⋮----\n1441\t\"\"\"Lock the quota row, then read the current-window rollup total fresh —\n1442\t    the atomic check-then-decide mechanism `POST /v1/events` uses to enforce\n1443\t    `R + Q <= L` without a TOCTOU race (plan §\"The atomic read-and-decide\").\n1444\t\n1445\t    Returns None when no quota row matches `(api_key_id, customer_id,\n1446\t    metric)` — the caller treats this as unlimited and takes no lock at all\n1447\t    (the common, zero-contention path).\n1448\t\n1449\t    **Two round-trips, deliberately, not one combined `LEFT JOIN ... FOR\n1450\t    UPDATE` statement.** `FOR UPDATE` only guarantees a fresh re-read of the\n1451\t    *locked* row itself (via PostgreSQL's `EvalPlanQual` recheck) when a\n1452\t    waiter unblocks after the lock holder commits — it does **not** force a\n1453\t    fresh snapshot for other tables read in the same statement, including a\n1454\t    `LEFT JOIN`. A waiter that queued for the lock before the holder\n1455\t    committed would evaluate that join against its own original (pre-wait)\n1456\t    snapshot and read a stale `total_quantity`, silently breaking strict\n1457\t    enforcement under real concurrency (verified empirically: a single\n1458\t    combined statement let every concurrent waiter read the same stale\n1459\t    total and all get admitted). Issuing the `usage_rollup` read as its own\n1460\t    statement *after* the lock is acquired gives it a fresh per-statement\n1461\t    READ COMMITTED snapshot, which does include everything the previous lock\n1462\t    holder just committed — this is what actually makes `current_total`\n1463\t    accurate for every waiter, not just the first, uncontended caller.\n1464\t    \"\"\"\n1465\tlock_result = await session.execute(\n1466\tlock_row = lock_result.mappings().first()\n1467\t⋮----\n1468\trollup_result = await session.execute(\n1469\trollup_row = rollup_result.mappings().first()\n1470\tcurrent_total = rollup_row[\"total_quantity\"] if rollup_row is not None else Decimal(0)\n1471\t</file>\n1472\t\n1473\t<file path=\"src/repositories/usage_repo.py\">\n1474\t\"\"\"Repository for reading `usage_rollup` — the O(1) aggregate lookup behind\n1475\t`GET /v1/usage`.\n1476\t\n1477\tReads the pre-aggregated counter rather than summing `events` live, which is\n1478\twhat keeps the GET p95 budget bounded as ingest volume grows (see the plan's\n1479\t\"why reading the rollup\" writeup).\n1480\t\"\"\"\n1481\t⋮----\n1482\t@dataclass(frozen=True)\n1483\tclass UsageRollupRecord\n1484\t⋮----\n1485\t\"\"\"The aggregate counter for one `(api_key_id, customer_id, metric, window_start)` bucket.\"\"\"\n1486\t⋮----\n1487\ttotal_quantity: Decimal\n1488\tevent_count: int\n1489\t⋮----\n1490\t\"\"\"Fetch the usage counter for a bucket, scoped by the authenticated\n1491\t    `api_key_id` first — an authenticated key can never read another\n1492\t    tenant's totals (IDOR/BOLA mitigation, AC17). None means no events have\n1493\t    landed in this bucket yet (the caller returns zeros, not 404).\"\"\"\n1494\tresult = await session.execute(\n1495\trow = result.mappings().first()\n1496\t</file>\n1497\t\n1498\t<file path=\"src/services/__init__.py\">\n1499\t\"\"\"Application services — orchestrate repositories inside a transaction per use case.\"\"\"\n1500\t</file>\n1501\t\n1502\t<file path=\"src/services/quota_service.py\">\n1503\t\"\"\"Service for `PUT /v1/quotas` — the admin-scoped upsert + 201/200 mapping.\n1504\t\n1505\tOrchestrates one transaction per request: the `xmax` upsert in\n1506\t`src/repositories/quotas_repo.py` reports create-vs-replace in a single\n1507\tround-trip, so this layer only maps that to the HTTP status and emits the\n1508\taudit-trail log (`quota.upsert`, plan §\"Repudiation\").\n1509\t\"\"\"\n1510\t⋮----\n1511\tlogger = get_logger(service=\"meterly\")\n1512\t⋮----\n1513\t@dataclass(frozen=True)\n1514\tclass QuotaUpsertOutcome\n1515\t⋮----\n1516\t\"\"\"The result of processing a `PUT /v1/quotas` request: the stored quota\n1517\t    and the HTTP status the route should return (201 create, 200 replace).\"\"\"\n1518\t⋮----\n1519\tcustomer_id: str\n1520\tmetric: str\n1521\tlimit_per_window: int\n1522\thttp_status: int\n1523\t⋮----\n1524\t\"\"\"Create-or-replace the cap for `(customer_id, metric)` under the\n1525\t    authenticated principal's own `api_key_id` — the server, never the\n1526\t    client, sets `api_key_id`, which is the mass-assignment protection\n1527\t    (ASVS 15.3.3) against writing another tenant's cap.\n1528\t    \"\"\"\n1529\t⋮----\n1530\trecord = await upsert_quota(\n1531\t⋮----\n1532\taction = \"create\" if record.inserted else \"replace\"\n1533\t⋮----\n1534\tdef to_response(outcome: QuotaUpsertOutcome) -> QuotaResponse\n1535\t⋮----\n1536\t\"\"\"Map the service outcome to the minimal public response shape (ASVS 15.3.1).\"\"\"\n1537\t</file>\n1538\t\n1539\t<file path=\"src/services/time_windows.py\">\n1540\t\"\"\"Hour-window flooring shared by the events and usage services.\n1541\t\n1542\t`date_trunc('hour', <timestamptz>)` is STABLE (not IMMUTABLE) in PostgreSQL —\n1543\tits result depends on the session `TimeZone` — so it cannot back a stored\n1544\tgenerated column. Flooring explicitly in UTC here sidesteps that timezone\n1545\ttrap entirely and is directly unit-testable.\n1546\t\"\"\"\n1547\t⋮----\n1548\tdef floor_to_hour_utc(timestamp: datetime) -> datetime\n1549\t⋮----\n1550\t\"\"\"Return `timestamp` floored to the start of its UTC hour.\n1551\t\n1552\t    Converts to UTC first if `timestamp` carries a different timezone, so the\n1553\t    result is always a UTC-normalized hour boundary regardless of the input's\n1554\t    original offset.\n1555\t    \"\"\"\n1556\tas_utc = timestamp.astimezone(timezone.utc)\n1557\t</file>\n1558\t\n1559\t<file path=\"src/services/usage_service.py\">\n1560\t\"\"\"Service for `GET /v1/usage` — the scoped rollup read + hour flooring.\n1561\t\n1562\tA missing bucket is a valid, common answer (zero usage), not an error — see\n1563\t`get_usage`'s docstring for why this must never become a 404.\n1564\t\"\"\"\n1565\t⋮----\n1566\tlogger = get_logger(service=\"meterly\")\n1567\t⋮----\n1568\t\"\"\"Return the aggregated usage counter for `(customer_id, metric, window)`.\n1569\t\n1570\t    A bucket with no recorded events returns zeros with a 200, never a 404 —\n1571\t    returning 404 would leak whether *any* tenant has data for that bucket,\n1572\t    and \"no usage yet\" is a legitimate steady state for a new customer.\n1573\t    \"\"\"\n1574\twindow_start = floor_to_hour_utc(query.window)\n1575\t⋮----\n1576\trollup = await find_usage_rollup(\n1577\t⋮----\n1578\ttotal_quantity = rollup.total_quantity if rollup is not None else Decimal(\"0\")\n1579\tevent_count = rollup.event_count if rollup is not None else 0\n1580\t</file>\n1581\t\n1582\t<file path=\"CLAUDE.md\">\n1583\t# Meterly\n1584\t\n1585\t## Stack\n1586\t- Cloud environment: AWS (ECS Fargate + RDS PostgreSQL + ALB), Terraform under infra/\n1587\t- Language/runtime: Python 3.12\n1588\t- Framework(s): FastAPI\n1589\t- Data stores: PostgreSQL\n1590\t- Migration tool: Alembic\n1591\t- Cloud / IaC: AWS + Terraform\n1592\t- Auth provider: API keys (Argon2id-hashed at rest), per-key rate limiting — no third-party IdP.\n1593\t  `api_keys.scope` (`'ingest'` default, `'admin'` elevated) gates `PUT /v1/quotas`; provision an\n1594\t  admin key with `scripts/seed_api_key.py --admin`.\n1595\t- Observability: CloudWatch + X-Ray + Sentry (release-tagged)\n1596\t- Packaging / runtime: container (Docker) — justified: deploys through the ECS canary path\n1597\t\n1598\t## How to run / build / test\n1599\t- Start: `uvicorn src.main:app --port 8000` (smoke check expects HTTP 200 at `http://localhost:8000/health`)\n1600\t- Test:  `pytest --cov=src --cov-branch`\n1601\t- Migrate: `alembic upgrade head` (run before deploying; also run locally after pulling schema changes)\n1602\t- Deploy: CI on merge — see docs/pipeline-deployment-targets.md (build-provenance → deploy.yml chain)\n1603\t\n1604\t## Frontend design source\n1605\t- Design source: none (API only)\n1606\t\n1607\t## Conventions\n1608\t- Module layout: src/ package (src/main.py app entry), facade modules per code-standards defaults\n1609\t- Test locations: tests/ as test_*.py\n1610\t\n1611\t## What \"done\" means\n1612\t- Smoke check passes, security report clean, tests pass at >= 85% coverage,\n1613\t  docs updated for touched directories, PR description written.\n1614\t\n1615\t<!--\n1616\t  REMEMBER per project: the smoke-check.sh hook reads Start/health values above.\n1617\t  Set them here, or export SMOKE_START_CMD / SMOKE_HEALTH_URL, or (frontend-only)\n1618\t  swap in the build-check variant of smoke-check.sh from the spec.\n1619\t-->\n1620\t</file>\n1621\t\n1622\t<file path=\"PROJECT.md\">\n1623\tFeature: usage CSV export.\n1624\t- GET /v1/usage/export returns the caller's usage rollups (customer_id, metric, window_start, total_quantity) as CSV.\n1625\t- Existing API-key auth applies. No behavior change to any existing endpoint.\n1626\tDesign source: none.\n1627\t</file>\n1628\t\n1629\t<file path=\"src/api/errors.py\">\n1630\t\"\"\"The error-envelope facade — every exception a handler raises terminates\n1631\there, at one centralized boundary, as the single response shape:\n1632\t`{\"error\": {\"code\", \"message\", \"requestId\"}}`.\n1633\t\n1634\tNever leaks a stack trace, exception type, SQL, or internal path to the\n1635\tclient (ASVS 16.5.1/16.5.3) — the detail is logged server-side and the client\n1636\tgets a generic, stable `code` plus the `requestId` that ties a user report\n1637\tback to the server log line.\n1638\t\"\"\"\n1639\t⋮----\n1640\tlogger = get_logger(service=\"meterly\")\n1641\t⋮----\n1642\t_STATUS_TO_CODE = {\n1643\t⋮----\n1644\tdef _request_id(request: Request) -> str\n1645\t⋮----\n1646\t\"\"\"Read the correlation id the logging middleware assigned to this request.\"\"\"\n1647\t⋮----\n1648\tdef _envelope(code: str, message: str, request_id: str) -> dict\n1649\t⋮----\n1650\t\"\"\"Build the one response shape every error returns.\"\"\"\n1651\t⋮----\n1652\tclass AppError(HTTPException)\n1653\t⋮----\n1654\t\"\"\"An `HTTPException` carrying an explicit `app_code`, for the cases where\n1655\t    `_STATUS_TO_CODE`'s status->code map can't express the distinction —\n1656\t    `429` already maps to `rate_limited` (the Tier-2 throttle), but a quota\n1657\t    rejection needs its own, distinct `quota_exceeded` code on the same\n1658\t    status. `handle_http_exception` prefers `app_code` over the status map\n1659\t    when present, so this is the minimal single-boundary extension rather\n1660\t    than reshaping the map itself.\n1661\t    \"\"\"\n1662\t⋮----\n1663\tdef __init__(self, status_code: int, *, app_code: str, detail: str, headers: dict | None = None) -> None\n1664\t⋮----\n1665\tdef register_error_handlers(app: FastAPI) -> None\n1666\t⋮----\n1667\t\"\"\"Register the centralized exception handlers on `app`.\n1668\t\n1669\t    Called once from `src/main.py` at app construction — no route ever builds\n1670\t    its own error response; it raises and lets this boundary map it.\n1671\t    \"\"\"\n1672\t⋮----\n1673\t@app.exception_handler(RequestValidationError)\n1674\t    async def handle_validation_error(request: Request, exc: RequestValidationError) -> JSONResponse\n1675\t⋮----\n1676\t\"\"\"Map Pydantic/FastAPI validation failures to 422 with a safe message.\"\"\"\n1677\trequest_id = _request_id(request)\n1678\t⋮----\n1679\t@app.exception_handler(StarletteHTTPException)\n1680\t    async def handle_http_exception(request: Request, exc: StarletteHTTPException) -> JSONResponse\n1681\t⋮----\n1682\t\"\"\"Map a raised `HTTPException` (auth, rate-limit, not-found, ...) to the envelope.\n1683\t\n1684\t        Prefers an explicit `app_code` (set by `AppError`) over the status->code\n1685\t        map — this is what lets two different exceptions share one HTTP status\n1686\t        (`429 rate_limited` vs. `429 quota_exceeded`) with distinct client-facing codes.\n1687\t        \"\"\"\n1688\t⋮----\n1689\tcode = getattr(exc, \"app_code\", None) or _STATUS_TO_CODE.get(exc.status_code, \"error\")\n1690\tmessage = exc.detail if isinstance(exc.detail, str) else \"request failed\"\n1691\t⋮----\n1692\t@app.exception_handler(Exception)\n1693\t    async def handle_unexpected_error(request: Request, exc: Exception) -> JSONResponse\n1694\t⋮----\n1695\t\"\"\"Catch-all: log the full detail server-side, return a generic 500 to the client.\n1696\t\n1697\t        This is the fail-closed boundary — an unhandled exception mid-write\n1698\t        never leaks stack/SQL/secret detail, and because the events + rollup\n1699\t        write happens in one transaction (`src/services/events_service.py`),\n1700\t        an exception here means that transaction was rolled back, not\n1701\t        partially applied.\n1702\t        \"\"\"\n1703\t⋮----\n1704\t__all__ = [\"register_error_handlers\", \"HTTPException\", \"AppError\"]\n1705\t</file>\n1706\t\n1707\t<file path=\"src/api/middleware.py\">\n1708\t\"\"\"Centralized edge middleware — security headers, CORS, the body-size guard,\n1709\tand the Tier-1 (pre-auth, IP+route-keyed) throttle.\n1710\t\n1711\tRegistered once at app construction (`src/main.py`) in the order\n1712\t`api-edge-conventions` specifies: request-id/trace, security headers, CORS,\n1713\tbody-size guard, Tier-1 throttle, auth guard, Tier-2 throttle, handler. No\n1714\troute re-declares any of this — a new endpoint inherits it by being mounted\n1715\ton the app.\n1716\t\"\"\"\n1717\t⋮----\n1718\tlogger = get_logger(service=\"meterly\")\n1719\t⋮----\n1720\t_SECURITY_HEADERS = {\n1721\t⋮----\n1722\tclass SecurityHeadersMiddleware(BaseHTTPMiddleware)\n1723\t⋮----\n1724\t\"\"\"Sets a fixed set of security headers on every response, including error responses.\"\"\"\n1725\t⋮----\n1726\t\"\"\"Run the request, then stamp the security header set onto the response.\"\"\"\n1727\tresponse = await call_next(request)\n1728\t⋮----\n1729\t# Usage totals are billing-adjacent personal-scoped data — never cache\n1730\t# them client-side or in an intermediary (ASVS 14.3.2).\n1731\t⋮----\n1732\tclass BodySizeLimitMiddleware(BaseHTTPMiddleware)\n1733\t⋮----\n1734\t\"\"\"Rejects a request whose `Content-Length` exceeds the configured cap with 413.\n1735\t\n1736\t    These payloads are tiny by design (a handful of scalar fields); an\n1737\t    unbounded body is a cheap denial-of-service vector worth rejecting before\n1738\t    it reaches any parsing.\n1739\t    \"\"\"\n1740\t⋮----\n1741\tdef __init__(self, app: FastAPI, *, max_body_size_bytes: int) -> None\n1742\t⋮----\n1743\t\"\"\"Check `Content-Length` before invoking the rest of the stack.\"\"\"\n1744\tcontent_length = request.headers.get(\"content-length\")\n1745\t⋮----\n1746\tpass  # malformed Content-Length falls through to normal request handling/validation\n1747\t⋮----\n1748\t# Paths exempt from the Tier-1 Redis throttle: the liveness probe must return\n1749\t# 200 with *zero* dependencies (no DB, no Redis) — it is the smoke check's and\n1750\t# the build-fallback's only signal, and gating it on Redis would make a cache\n1751\t# outage look like a total application outage (plan §\"health split\").\n1752\t_TIER1_EXEMPT_PATHS = frozenset({\"/health\"})\n1753\t⋮----\n1754\tclass Tier1EdgeThrottleMiddleware(BaseHTTPMiddleware)\n1755\t⋮----\n1756\t\"\"\"Pre-auth, IP+route-keyed Redis token bucket — sheds an anonymous flood\n1757\t    before the request can spend an Argon2id verification (mitigates D1/D3).\n1758\t    \"\"\"\n1759\t⋮----\n1760\tdef __init__(self, app: FastAPI, *, capacity: int, refill_rate_per_second: float) -> None\n1761\t⋮----\n1762\t\"\"\"Consume one token from the `client_ip:route` bucket before proceeding.\n1763\t\n1764\t        Fails **open** (allows the request, logs a warning) on a Redis\n1765\t        connection error rather than 500ing every request — an unreachable\n1766\t        cache degrading to \"temporarily unlimited\" is preferable to a full\n1767\t        outage of the ingest path; Tier-2's per-key bucket and the underlying\n1768\t        DB constraints remain the durable protections either way.\n1769\t        \"\"\"\n1770\t⋮----\n1771\tclient_ip = request.client.host if request.client else \"unknown\"\n1772\tbucket_identity = f\"{client_ip}:{request.url.path}\"\n1773\t⋮----\n1774\tdecision = await get_tier1_limiter().check(\n1775\texcept Exception:  # noqa: BLE001 - a Redis outage must not take down the whole API\n1776\t⋮----\n1777\tdef configure_cors(app: FastAPI, settings: Settings) -> None\n1778\t⋮----\n1779\t\"\"\"Register the CORS middleware with an explicit origin allowlist from config.\n1780\t\n1781\t    Defaults to an empty allowlist (this is a server-to-server API, not a\n1782\t    browser client) rather than `*` — `api-edge-conventions` forbids\n1783\t    reflecting an arbitrary origin.\n1784\t    \"\"\"\n1785\t</file>\n1786\t\n1787\t<file path=\"src/api/README.md\">\n1788\t# src/api/\n1789\t\n1790\t## Purpose\n1791\t\n1792\tHTTP API layer: FastAPI route handlers, request/response schemas (Pydantic v2), error envelope boundary, and edge-concern middleware (request ID, security headers, CORS, body-size guards).\n1793\t\n1794\t## Modules\n1795\t\n1796\t| File / Module | Responsibility |\n1797\t|---|---|\n1798\t| `routes/events.py` | `POST /v1/events` handler; calls `events_service.create_event`. |\n1799\t| `routes/usage.py` | `GET /v1/usage` handler; calls `usage_service.read_usage`. |\n1800\t| `routes/quotas.py` | `PUT /v1/quotas` handler; composes auth -> Tier-2 throttle -> an `admin`-scope gate (403 `forbidden` otherwise) -> `quota_service.upsert_tenant_quota`. |\n1801\t| `routes/health.py` | `GET /health` (liveness, no dependencies) and `GET /health/ready` (readiness, DB + migration check). |\n1802\t| `schemas/events.py` | Pydantic models for POST /v1/events request and response; `extra='forbid'` contract enforcement. |\n1803\t| `schemas/usage.py` | Pydantic models for GET /v1/usage request (query parameters) and response. |\n1804\t| `schemas/quotas.py` | Pydantic models for PUT /v1/quotas request (`customer_id`, `metric`, `limit_per_window`, `extra='forbid'`) and response (echo shape). |\n1805\t| `middleware.py` | Request-ID / trace-ID assignment, security headers (HSTS, CSP, X-Frame-Options), CORS (allows GET/POST/PUT). |\n1806\t| `errors.py` | Error-envelope boundary: catches all unhandled exceptions and returns `{error:{code,message,requestId}}` with no stack/secret leakage. `AppError` lets a raised exception carry an explicit `app_code` (e.g. `quota_exceeded`) that overrides the default status->code map — needed because 429 is shared by two distinct codes (`rate_limited` vs `quota_exceeded`). |\n1807\t\n1808\t## Relationships\n1809\t\n1810\t**Public surface:**\n1811\t- Imported by `src/main.py` to register routes with FastAPI.\n1812\t- Exposes `get_app()` function which returns the fully-configured FastAPI instance.\n1813\t\n1814\t**Dependencies:**\n1815\t- `middleware.py` and `errors.py` are registered once at app construction (middleware stack + exception handler).\n1816\t- Each route handler uses `require_api_key` guard from `src/auth` to enforce authentication.\n1817\t- Route handlers call `src/services.{events_service, usage_service}` to execute business logic.\n1818\t- Schemas validate request bodies/parameters; malformed input raises Pydantic `ValidationError` → 422.\n1819\t- Middleware and error boundary run for all routes, ensuring every response has proper headers and envelope shape.\n1820\t\n1821\t**Middleware ordering (in `main.py`):**\n1822\t1. Request-ID / trace (outermost) — sets correlation context for all downstream logging.\n1823\t2. Security headers — applied to every response.\n1824\t3. CORS — explicit allowlist from config.\n1825\t4. Body-size guard — reject Content-Length > 8 KiB.\n1826\t5. Tier-1 edge throttle (pre-auth) — IP+route keyed.\n1827\t6. `require_api_key` guard — auth.\n1828\t7. Tier-2 per-key throttle (post-auth) — api_key_id keyed.\n1829\t8. Route handler (innermost) — wrapped by error-envelope boundary.\n1830\t\n1831\t## Notes\n1832\t\n1833\t**Contract enforcement:**\n1834\t- Request bodies are validated against Pydantic schemas; `extra='forbid'` rejects unknown fields.\n1835\t- All string fields are bounded length (e.g., `customer_id` ≤128, `metric` ≤64).\n1836\t- `quantity` is a decimal > 0 (no zero or negative); `idempotency_key` is alphanumeric + underscore/dash.\n1837\t- GET `/v1/usage` requires a timezone-aware ISO-8601 `window` parameter within 90 days past to 1 hour future (naive datetimes rejected).\n1838\t- PUT `/v1/quotas`: `limit_per_window` is an integer `>= 1` (`<= 1e15`, BIGINT-safe); `customer_id`/`metric` reuse the same anchored allowlists as events; unknown fields (including a client-supplied `api_key_id`/`scope`) are rejected outright.\n1839\t\n1840\t**Error handling:**\n1841\t- Authentication failures (missing/invalid key) → 401/403 before handlers run.\n1842\t- `PUT /v1/quotas` from a non-`admin`-scoped key → 403 `forbidden` (function-level authorization, checked in the route's composed dependency).\n1843\t- Rate-limit exceeded (Tier-1 or Tier-2) → 429 `rate_limited` + Retry-After header.\n1844\t- `POST /v1/events` over its quota → 429 `quota_exceeded` (distinct code, same status) + Retry-After to the next hour boundary; no event/rollup written (transaction rolled back).\n1845\t- Schema validation failure → 422 with Pydantic error detail.\n1846\t- Database errors (constraint violation, connection drop) → caught by error envelope → 500 (generic message, safe).\n1847\t- Any unhandled exception → error envelope → 500, safe, no leak.\n1848\t\n1849\t**Security headers (all responses):**\n1850\t- `Strict-Transport-Security: max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains` (production only; localhost omitted).\n1851\t- `X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff` — disable MIME sniffing.\n1852\t- `X-Frame-Options: DENY` — no embedding in iframes.\n1853\t- `Cache-Control: no-store, no-cache, must-revalidate, max-age=0` (API, not HTML).\n1854\t</file>\n1855\t\n1856\t<file path=\"src/auth/api_key.py\">\n1857\t\"\"\"Split-token API-key parsing and Argon2id verification against `api_keys`.\n1858\t\n1859\tKey format: `mtr_live_<key_id>_<secret>` — `key_id` is a public, indexed lookup\n1860\thandle; `secret` is a >=128-bit CSPRNG value whose Argon2id hash is the only\n1861\tthing stored. Parsing is a strict anchored regex so a malformed header is\n1862\trejected before any database work (`src/api/schemas` sibling contract for the\n1863\t`Authorization` header, per the plan's validation-contract table).\n1864\t\"\"\"\n1865\t⋮----\n1866\t_TOKEN_PATTERN = re.compile(r\"^mtr_live_(?P<key_id>[A-Za-z0-9]{1,32})_(?P<secret>[A-Za-z0-9]{1,64})$\")\n1867\t_KEY_ID_BYTES = 16\n1868\t_SECRET_BYTES = 32\n1869\t⋮----\n1870\t@dataclass(frozen=True)\n1871\tclass ParsedApiKey\n1872\t⋮----\n1873\t\"\"\"The two halves of a presented split-token API key.\"\"\"\n1874\t⋮----\n1875\tkey_id: str\n1876\tsecret: str\n1877\t⋮----\n1878\t@dataclass(frozen=True)\n1879\tclass AuthenticatedPrincipal\n1880\t⋮----\n1881\t\"\"\"The authenticated caller: the internal `api_key_id`, its rate-limit\n1882\t    budget, and its authorization `scope`.\n1883\t\n1884\t    `scope` defaults to `\"ingest\"` so any direct construction in existing unit\n1885\t    tests keeps working unchanged; `verify_api_key` always populates it\n1886\t    explicitly from the stored record. `\"admin\"` is a superset scope — an\n1887\t    admin-scoped key may do everything an ingest key does, plus call\n1888\t    `PUT /v1/quotas` (plan §\"The tenant model\").\n1889\t    \"\"\"\n1890\t⋮----\n1891\tapi_key_id: int\n1892\trate_limit_per_sec: int\n1893\tscope: str = \"ingest\"\n1894\t⋮----\n1895\tdef parse_split_token(presented_key: str) -> ParsedApiKey | None\n1896\t⋮----\n1897\t\"\"\"Parse `mtr_live_<key_id>_<secret>`; returns None for anything malformed.\n1898\t\n1899\t    A strict, anchored regex means a malformed token is rejected before any\n1900\t    database work — no scanning, no partial parse (401 before any DB work).\n1901\t    \"\"\"\n1902\tmatch = _TOKEN_PATTERN.match(presented_key)\n1903\t⋮----\n1904\t\"\"\"Verify a presented `Authorization` bearer value end to end.\n1905\t\n1906\t    Parses the split token, looks the key up by its public `key_id`, and runs\n1907\t    an Argon2id verify against the stored hash. Returns None on any failure —\n1908\t    malformed token, unknown/revoked key_id, or a wrong secret are all\n1909\t    indistinguishable to the caller (no oracle for key enumeration).\n1910\t    \"\"\"\n1911\tparsed = parse_split_token(presented_key)\n1912\t⋮----\n1913\trecord = await find_active_key_by_key_id(connection, parsed.key_id)\n1914\t⋮----\n1915\tdef generate_split_token() -> tuple[str, str, str]\n1916\t⋮----\n1917\t\"\"\"Generate a new `(key_id, secret, presented_key)` triple for key\n1918\t    provisioning (`scripts/seed_api_key.py`).\n1919\t\n1920\t    `secret_hash = hash_secret(secret)` is what the caller stores; `secret`\n1921\t    and the full `presented_key` are shown to the operator exactly once and\n1922\t    never persisted in plaintext.\n1923\t    \"\"\"\n1924\tkey_id = secrets.token_hex(_KEY_ID_BYTES)\n1925\tsecret = secrets.token_hex(_SECRET_BYTES)\n1926\tpresented_key = f\"mtr_live_{key_id}_{secret}\"\n1927\t⋮----\n1928\tdef hash_new_secret(secret: str) -> str\n1929\t⋮----\n1930\t\"\"\"Hash a freshly generated secret for storage — thin re-export of the\n1931\t    crypto facade so callers of this module don't need a second import.\"\"\"\n1932\t</file>\n1933\t\n1934\t<file path=\"src/auth/README.md\">\n1935\t# src/auth/\n1936\t\n1937\t## Purpose\n1938\t\n1939\tAuthentication and authorization layer: API key verification (split-token parsing and Argon2id credential check), in-process verification cache for performance, and Redis-backed rate limiting (Tier-1 pre-auth and Tier-2 post-auth, both fail-open).\n1940\t\n1941\t## Modules\n1942\t\n1943\t| File / Module | Responsibility |\n1944\t|---|---|\n1945\t| `__init__.py` | `require_api_key` FastAPI dependency guard: parses the `Authorization: Bearer` header, checks the verification cache, falls back to DB lookup + Argon2id verify on cache miss, sets the authenticated `api_key_id` in request state. |\n1946\t| `api_key.py` | Split-token key parsing (`mtr_live_<key_id>_<secret>`), verification logic (Argon2id check), cache TTL management, revocation status check. `AuthenticatedPrincipal.scope` (`\"ingest\"` default, `\"admin\"` elevated) rides the same cached principal. |\n1947\t| `rate_limit.py` | Tier-1 (pre-auth, IP+route keyed) and Tier-2 (post-auth, api_key_id keyed) Redis token-bucket limiters; both fail open (log warning, allow request) on Redis connection error. |\n1948\t\n1949\t**Authorization scope (function-level, on top of authentication):**\n1950\t- `AuthenticatedPrincipal.scope` is `\"ingest\"` by default; `\"admin\"` is a superset scope, not a separate key family — an admin-scoped key does everything an ingest key does, plus is permitted to call `PUT /v1/quotas`.\n1951\t- Only `src/api/routes/quotas.py`'s composed dependency checks `scope` (`principal.scope == \"admin\"`, else `HTTPException(403)`); every other route ignores it, so existing behavior is unchanged.\n1952\t- Provisioned via `scripts/seed_api_key.py --admin` (defaults to `\"ingest\"` without the flag); this is also the DAST-context admin test key (DAST-3).\n1953\t\n1954\t## Relationships\n1955\t\n1956\t**Public surface:**\n1957\t- `require_api_key` is imported by `src/api.routes` as a FastAPI dependency (guard). When used, it populates `request.state.api_key_id` with the authenticated principal's ID.\n1958\t- Tier-1 and Tier-2 rate limiters are called from `src/api.middleware` (Tier-1) and `src/api.routes.{events, usage}` (Tier-2).\n1959\t\n1960\t**Dependencies:**\n1961\t- `api_key.py` imports `src.crypto` for Argon2id verify and `src.db.session_context` for credential lookup on cache miss.\n1962\t- `api_key.py` imports `src.logging.get_logger` for debug/warning logs (e.g., revocation, cache miss).\n1963\t- `rate_limit.py` imports `src.config.settings` for rate limits (per-key `rate_limit_per_sec`) and `src.redis_client` for token-bucket state.\n1964\t- Both modules are async (return coroutines for use in async context).\n1965\t\n1966\t**Request flow:**\n1967\t1. **Tier-1 throttle** (IP+route keyed) runs first in middleware, pre-auth. Checks Redis, fails open.\n1968\t2. **`require_api_key`** parses and verifies the split token, caches verified keys.\n1969\t3. **Tier-2 throttle** (api_key_id keyed) runs post-auth. Checks Redis with the now-authenticated principal's ID, fails open.\n1970\t4. If any throttle rejects (rate limit exceeded), the handler never runs; 429 is returned.\n1971\t\n1972\t## Notes\n1973\t\n1974\t**Verification cache:**\n1975\t- In-process TTL-bounded cache (default: 5 minutes) keyed on the public `key_id` (not the secret).\n1976\t- On cache hit, constant-time comparison of the cached secret against the request secret (no Argon2id cost).\n1977\t- On cache miss, DB lookup + Argon2id verify (expensive, ~100ms), then store in cache for future hits.\n1978\t- Cache is per-process; horizontal scale-out (multiple Fargate tasks) means cache hit rates vary per task (not a correctness issue, just a performance variance).\n1979\t\n1980\t**Revocation:**\n1981\t- API key lookup checks the `revoked_at` column; a non-null value means the key is revoked.\n1982\t- Revoked keys are rejected with 403 and not cached.\n1983\t- Cache invalidation is not real-time (revocations take up to 5 minutes to propagate across all tasks).\n1984\t- Recorded in `.pipeline/plan.md` as an accepted risk (noted for future key-revocation SLA if tighter bounds are needed).\n1985\t\n1986\t**Rate limiting — fail-open behavior:**\n1987\t- If Redis is unavailable, a Redis `ConnectionError` is caught and logged as a warning.\n1988\t- The request is allowed through (traffic is not dropped).\n1989\t- Recorded in `.pipeline/surface-delta.md` as an availability tradeoff: prefer dropping rate limits over dropping user requests.\n1990\t\n1991\t**Rate limiting — Tier-1 pre-auth:**\n1992\t- Keyed on IP + route (e.g., `ratelimit:tier1:POST:/v1/events:192.0.2.1`).\n1993\t- Limits apply per route (different budgets can be configured per route if needed).\n1994\t- Protects against flooding *before* we pay an Argon2id cost.\n1995\t- Runs in middleware; all routes inherit the same policy.\n1996\t\n1997\t**Rate limiting — Tier-2 post-auth:**\n1998\t- Keyed on `api_key_id` (e.g., `ratelimit:tier2:123`).\n1999\t- Limit is the key's `rate_limit_per_sec` column (default: 100 req/s).\n2000\t- Per-customer isolation: two customers sharing one client IP each get independent buckets (discriminating test in `tests/integration/test_rate_limit.py`).\n2001\t- Runs after auth in the route handler; only affects authenticated requests.\n2002\t</file>\n2003\t\n2004\t<file path=\"src/db/README.md\">\n2005\t# src/db/\n2006\t\n2007\t## Purpose\n2008\t\n2009\tDatabase connectivity and session management: async SQLAlchemy session factory, connection pooling, transaction scope, and per-transaction RLS context setup.\n2010\t\n2011\t## Modules\n2012\t\n2013\t| File / Module | Responsibility |\n2014\t|---|---|\n2015\t| `session.py` | `session_context(api_key_id)` — async context manager that opens a transactional AsyncSession, sets the RLS context variable, and yields the session. Used by services to run queries with both transaction and RLS guarantees. |\n2016\t\n2017\t## Relationships\n2018\t\n2019\t**Public surface:**\n2020\t- `session_context` is imported by `src/services.{events_service, usage_service}` to create transactional scopes for queries.\n2021\t\n2022\t**Dependencies:**\n2023\t- Imports `src.config.settings` for the `DATABASE_URL` (async connection string).\n2024\t- Imports SQLAlchemy's async engine/session machinery.\n2025\t\n2026\t**RLS mechanism:**\n2027\t- At the start of each transaction (entered via `async with session_context(api_key_id)`), the context manager executes `SET LOCAL app.current_api_key_id = :api_key_id`.\n2028\t- This PostgreSQL session variable is read by the RLS policy on every table access within the transaction.\n2029\t- The `SET LOCAL` is per-transaction, so the context is automatically cleared at commit (no cleanup needed).\n2030\t- This ensures that even if a repository query accidentally omits the `api_key_id` filter, RLS blocks the access (defense-in-depth).\n2031\t\n2032\t## Notes\n2033\t\n2034\t**Isolation level (explicit pin):**\n2035\t- `get_engine()` pins `isolation_level=\"READ COMMITTED\"` on the async engine rather than\n2036\t  inheriting the DB/role default. `src/repositories/quotas_repo.py`'s\n2037\t  `read_tenant_quota_state_locked` locks the `quotas` row (`SELECT ... FOR UPDATE`) then\n2038\t  reads `usage_rollup` as a **separate** statement; that second read only sees the prior\n2039\t  lock holder's committed increment because each statement gets a fresh snapshot under\n2040\t  READ COMMITTED. Under REPEATABLE READ a lock-waiter would read a stale rollup total and\n2041\t  admit events past the quota cap. Regression-guarded by `tests/test_db_session_isolation.py`.\n2042\t\n2043\t**Connection pooling:**\n2044\t- The async engine uses a connection pool (default: 5-20 connections).\n2045\t- At startup (lifespan in `src/main.py`), the pool is created and warmed.\n2046\t- At shutdown, all connections are drained and closed (graceful shutdown).\n2047\t\n2048\t**Transaction scope:**\n2049\t- Every service call wraps its queries in a `session_context` block, ensuring all queries are in one transaction.\n2050\t- For `create_event`, both the event insert and the rollup upsert happen in the same transaction (atomicity).\n2051\t- For `read_usage`, the single SELECT is in its own transaction (isolation).\n2052\t\n2053\t**Async pattern:**\n2054\t- The session is async; all I/O operations (execute, fetch, etc.) are awaited.\n2055\t- The context manager is async (uses `async with`).\n2056\t- Services must be async to use the context manager (all routes in `src/api` are async).\n2057\t\n2058\t**Database connection string:**\n2059\t- Expected in the `DATABASE_URL` environment variable.\n2060\t- Must be an async URL (e.g., `postgresql+asyncpg://...`).\n2061\t- Credentials are fetched by `src/config.secrets.fetch_db_credentials()` from AWS Secrets Manager at startup (or from `DATABASE_URL` if that's set).\n2062\t</file>\n2063\t\n2064\t<file path=\"src/db/session.py\">\n2065\t\"\"\"Async database engine/session management.\n2066\t\n2067\tThe engine is created lazily (on first use / at lifespan startup), never at\n2068\timport time — this is what lets `import src.main` succeed in the smoke-check\n2069\tbuild-fallback mode with no database reachable. Every request runs inside a\n2070\ttransaction that sets `app.current_api_key_id` via `SET LOCAL`, which backs the\n2071\tPostgreSQL row-level-security policy on `events`/`usage_rollup` (defense in\n2072\tdepth behind the application-level `api_key_id` scoping every repository query\n2073\talready applies).\n2074\t\"\"\"\n2075\t⋮----\n2076\t_engine: AsyncEngine | None = None\n2077\t_session_factory: async_sessionmaker[AsyncSession] | None = None\n2078\t⋮----\n2079\tdef get_engine() -> AsyncEngine\n2080\t⋮----\n2081\t\"\"\"Return the process-wide async engine, creating it on first call.\n2082\t\n2083\t    Deferred creation (rather than at import time) keeps `import src.main`\n2084\t    dependency-free for the smoke-check build-fallback path.\n2085\t    \"\"\"\n2086\t⋮----\n2087\t_engine = create_async_engine(\n2088\t⋮----\n2089\t# Pin READ COMMITTED explicitly rather than inheriting the DB/role\n2090\t# default. quotas_repo.read_tenant_quota_state_locked locks the\n2091\t# quotas row (SELECT ... FOR UPDATE) then reads usage_rollup in a\n2092\t# SEPARATE statement; that read only sees the prior lock holder's\n2093\t# committed increment because each statement gets a fresh snapshot\n2094\t# under READ COMMITTED. Under REPEATABLE READ a lock-waiter would\n2095\t# read a stale rollup total and admit events past the quota cap\n2096\t# (see the read_tenant_quota_state_locked docstring).\n2097\t⋮----\n2098\tdef get_session_factory() -> async_sessionmaker[AsyncSession]\n2099\t⋮----\n2100\t\"\"\"Return the process-wide session factory, creating it on first call.\"\"\"\n2101\t⋮----\n2102\t_session_factory = async_sessionmaker(get_engine(), expire_on_commit=False)\n2103\t⋮----\n2104\t@asynccontextmanager\n2105\tasync def scoped_transaction(api_key_id: int) -> AsyncIterator[AsyncSession]\n2106\t⋮----\n2107\t\"\"\"Open a transaction scoped to the authenticated `api_key_id`.\n2108\t\n2109\t    Sets `app.current_api_key_id` with `SET LOCAL` at the start of the\n2110\t    transaction so the PostgreSQL RLS policy backstop applies even if a\n2111\t    repository query were ever missing its own `api_key_id` filter. The\n2112\t    setting is transaction-local and is discarded automatically on commit/\n2113\t    rollback.\n2114\t    \"\"\"\n2115\tsession_factory = get_session_factory()\n2116\t⋮----\n2117\tdef _set_local_statement()\n2118\t⋮----\n2119\t\"\"\"Build the `SET LOCAL` statement for the current-tenant RLS setting.\n2120\t\n2121\t    A separate function keeps the (slightly unusual) `set_config` call —\n2122\t    `SET LOCAL` does not accept a bound parameter directly in all drivers —\n2123\t    isolated and documented in one place.\n2124\t    \"\"\"\n2125\t⋮----\n2126\tasync def dispose_engine() -> None\n2127\t⋮----\n2128\t\"\"\"Dispose of the engine's connection pool (called from lifespan shutdown).\"\"\"\n2129\t⋮----\n2130\t_engine = None\n2131\t_session_factory = None\n2132\t⋮----\n2133\tasync def check_database_ready() -> bool\n2134\t⋮----\n2135\t\"\"\"Run a fast `SELECT 1` to back the `/health/ready` readiness probe.\"\"\"\n2136\t⋮----\n2137\texcept Exception:  # noqa: BLE001 - readiness must never raise, only report False\n2138\t</file>\n2139\t\n2140\t<file path=\"src/main.py\">\n2141\t\"\"\"Application entry point: constructs the FastAPI app, registers the\n2142\tmiddleware stack in the order `api-edge-conventions` requires, mounts the\n2143\trouters, and wires the lifespan startup/shutdown hooks.\n2144\t\n2145\tDeliberately defers every *connecting* dependency (DB pool, Redis client) to\n2146\tfirst use rather than import time, so `python -c \"import src.main\"` succeeds\n2147\twith no PostgreSQL or Redis running — the smoke check's build-fallback mode\n2148\tdepends on this. OTel/Sentry instrumentation is wired during app construction\n2149\tinstead of inside the lifespan startup hook: Starlette forbids registering\n2150\tASGI middleware (which `FastAPIInstrumentor` does) once the app has started\n2151\tserving, and neither call performs a blocking network operation at\n2152\tconfiguration time — exporting is async/background and a no-op when\n2153\tunconfigured (`src/observability/otel.py`, `src/observability/sentry.py`).\n2154\t\"\"\"\n2155\t⋮----\n2156\tlogger = get_logger(service=\"meterly\")\n2157\t⋮----\n2158\t@asynccontextmanager\n2159\tasync def lifespan(app: FastAPI) -> AsyncIterator[None]\n2160\t⋮----\n2161\t\"\"\"Startup: log readiness (DB/Redis pools are created lazily on first use,\n2162\t    not here, so a slow/unreachable dependency at boot never blocks the\n2163\t    process from becoming live). Shutdown: drain and close pools.\n2164\t    \"\"\"\n2165\tsettings = get_settings()\n2166\t⋮----\n2167\tdef create_app() -> FastAPI\n2168\t⋮----\n2169\t\"\"\"Build and configure the FastAPI application (the single app-construction\n2170\t    entry point — nothing outside this function registers middleware or routes).\"\"\"\n2171\t⋮----\n2172\tapp = FastAPI(\n2173\t⋮----\n2174\t# Middleware is applied in reverse-registration order by Starlette (the\n2175\t# last `add_middleware` call becomes the outermost layer), so this list\n2176\t# is written outermost-to-innermost per api-edge-conventions and then\n2177\t# reversed at registration to preserve that intent.\n2178\t⋮----\n2179\t# Must run after routes are mounted (FastAPIInstrumentor introspects them)\n2180\t# and before the app starts serving (it registers ASGI middleware, which\n2181\t# Starlette forbids once serving has begun) — so construction time, not\n2182\t# the lifespan hook, is the correct place for this.\n2183\t⋮----\n2184\tapp = create_app()\n2185\t</file>\n2186\t\n2187\t<file path=\"src/repositories/api_keys_repo.py\">\n2188\t\"\"\"Repository for `api_keys` — the split-token lookup by `key_id`.\n2189\t\n2190\tThis is the one repository that legitimately queries by something other than\n2191\t`api_key_id` (it is *how* `api_key_id` gets resolved from a presented token),\n2192\tso it is exempt from the row-level-security scoping rule the other\n2193\trepositories enforce — there is no tenant scope yet at this point in the\n2194\trequest.\n2195\t\"\"\"\n2196\t⋮----\n2197\t@dataclass(frozen=True)\n2198\tclass ApiKeyRecord\n2199\t⋮----\n2200\t\"\"\"A row from `api_keys`, the fields the auth guard needs to verify a request.\"\"\"\n2201\t⋮----\n2202\tid: int\n2203\tkey_id: str\n2204\tsecret_hash: str\n2205\trate_limit_per_sec: int\n2206\trevoked_at: object | None\n2207\tscope: str\n2208\t⋮----\n2209\t\"\"\"Look up a non-revoked API key by its public `key_id` handle.\n2210\t\n2211\t    Returns None if no matching, non-revoked key exists — the caller (the\n2212\t    auth guard) treats that identically to a failed secret verification so\n2213\t    key enumeration can't be distinguished from a wrong secret.\n2214\t    \"\"\"\n2215\tresult = await connection.execute(\n2216\trow = result.mappings().first()\n2217\t⋮----\n2218\t\"\"\"Insert a new API key row (secret already hashed by the caller) and\n2219\t    return its internal surrogate id. Used only by `scripts/seed_api_key.py`\n2220\t    — there is no key-creation HTTP endpoint in this build's scope.\n2221\t\n2222\t    `scope` defaults to `'ingest'` so every existing caller of this function\n2223\t    is unaffected; pass `scope='admin'` to provision a key that may also call\n2224\t    `PUT /v1/quotas` (admin is a superset scope, not a separate key family).\n2225\t    \"\"\"\n2226\t</file>\n2227\t\n2228\t<file path=\"src/repositories/README.md\">\n2229\t# src/repositories/\n2230\t\n2231\t## Purpose\n2232\t\n2233\tData access layer: SQL queries with parameterization, row-level scoping (by authenticated `api_key_id`), and minimal-field projections. All database I/O is encapsulated here.\n2234\t\n2235\t## Modules\n2236\t\n2237\t| File / Module | Responsibility |\n2238\t|---|---|\n2239\t| `events_repo.py` | `create_or_replay_event(api_key_id, customer_id, metric, quantity, idempotency_key, window_start)` — INSERT ... ON CONFLICT ... DO NOTHING (idempotency). Also `upsert_rollup()` (called only on insert success). |\n2240\t| `usage_repo.py` | `read_usage(api_key_id, customer_id, metric, window_start)` — SELECT from `usage_rollup` scoped by `api_key_id`. Returns None if missing (caller handles zero conversion). |\n2241\t| `api_keys_repo.py` | `find_active_key_by_key_id(key_id)` — SELECT from `api_keys` by public `key_id` (used by auth cache miss); returns the full row including `scope`. `create_api_key(..., scope=\"ingest\")` — the only key-provisioning path. |\n2242\t| `quotas_repo.py` | `upsert_quota(...)` — `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT (api_key_id, customer_id, metric) DO UPDATE ... RETURNING (xmax = 0) AS inserted`, reporting create-vs-replace in one round-trip. `read_tenant_quota_state_locked(...)` — the atomic check-then-decide: locks the quota row (`FOR UPDATE`), then reads the current-window rollup total as a **separate, fresh** statement (see *Notes* below for why). Returns `None` when no quota exists (unlimited, no lock taken). |\n2243\t\n2244\t## Relationships\n2245\t\n2246\t**Public surface:**\n2247\t- Imported by `src/services.{events_service, usage_service, quota_service}` to execute queries.\n2248\t- `api_keys_repo` is also imported by `src/auth.api_key` (credential lookup on cache miss).\n2249\t- `quotas_repo` is imported by both `quota_service` (the upsert) and `events_service` (the read-and-decide).\n2250\t\n2251\t**Dependencies:**\n2252\t- All functions are async; they receive an `AsyncSession` from the service layer (obtained via `src/db.session_context`).\n2253\t- Queries use SQLAlchemy ORM with bound parameters (no string concatenation); all user input is parameterized.\n2254\t- RLS is set per-transaction by `src/db.session_context` before the first query runs (sets the `app.current_api_key_id` PostgreSQL context variable).\n2255\t\n2256\t**Row-level security:**\n2257\t- Every query includes the authenticated `api_key_id` in the WHERE clause (primary application-layer control).\n2258\t- E.g., `WHERE api_key_id = :auth_key AND customer_id = :customer_id` — no unscoped queries.\n2259\t- PostgreSQL RLS policy (`USING (api_key_id = current_setting(...))`) is the backstop; the app role has no `BYPASSRLS`.\n2260\t- If a query accidentally omits the `api_key_id` filter, RLS blocks it at the database level (defense-in-depth).\n2261\t\n2262\t**Field projections (minimal surface):**\n2263\t- `create_or_replay_event` returns only `{event_id, customer_id, metric, quantity, window_start, idempotent_replay}` — not the full row (which includes `created_at`, `event_time`, `api_key_id`).\n2264\t- `read_usage` returns only `{customer_id, metric, window_start, total_quantity, event_count}` — not internal bookkeeping (`updated_at`, `api_key_id`).\n2265\t- `api_keys_repo.get_by_key_id` returns the full row (needed by auth for `secret_hash`, `rate_limit_per_sec`, `revoked_at`).\n2266\t\n2267\t**Constraint enforcement:**\n2268\t- `create_or_replay_event` relies on the `UNIQUE (api_key_id, idempotency_key)` constraint at the DB level to detect duplicates.\n2269\t- If a duplicate key is encountered, PostgreSQL raises an `IntegrityError` (caught by service layer) → the service reads the original row instead.\n2270\t- `quantity > 0` and other domain constraints are enforced by CHECK constraints in the schema (verified at insert time).\n2271\t\n2272\t## Notes\n2273\t\n2274\t**ON CONFLICT pattern:**\n2275\t- The idempotency mechanism uses `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT (api_key_id, idempotency_key) DO NOTHING RETURNING id, ...`.\n2276\t- If the unique constraint is violated, the INSERT returns no rows.\n2277\t- The service layer checks `if result` — if a row was returned, this request won the insert; if not, a duplicate is detected.\n2278\t\n2279\t**RLS context setup:**\n2280\t- Before any query, `src/db.session_context` sets `SET LOCAL app.current_api_key_id = :id` in the transaction.\n2281\t- This context variable is read by the PostgreSQL RLS policy on every table access.\n2282\t- The `SET LOCAL` is per-transaction (automatically cleared at commit), so no context leakage across requests.\n2283\t\n2284\t**Quota lock-then-read pattern (why it's two statements, not one):**\n2285\t- `read_tenant_quota_state_locked` deliberately issues the `FOR UPDATE` lock on `quotas` and the `usage_rollup` read as two separate statements, not a single `LEFT JOIN ... FOR UPDATE OF q` query.\n2286\t- PostgreSQL's `FOR UPDATE` only forces a fresh re-check (`EvalPlanQual`) of the *locked* row itself when a blocked waiter unblocks after the holder commits — it does **not** force a fresh snapshot for another table read in the same statement, including a joined one.\n2287\t- A single combined statement lets a waiter that queued before the holder committed read `usage_rollup` from its own stale pre-wait snapshot — verified empirically during implementation: every concurrent waiter read the same stale total and all got admitted, silently breaking the cap.\n2288\t- Issuing the `usage_rollup` read as its own statement *after* the lock is acquired gives it a fresh READ COMMITTED snapshot that does include everything the previous holder just committed — this is what makes `current_total` accurate for every waiter, not just the first uncontended caller (`tests/integration/test_quota_concurrency.py`).\n2289\t\n2290\t**Async pattern:**\n2291\t- All functions are async; they use `await session.execute(...)` for queries.\n2292\t- They receive an `AsyncSession` that's already connected and in a transaction (setup by `src/db.session_context`).\n2293\t- No explicit connection management in the repo; the session is provided by the caller.\n2294\t</file>\n2295\t\n2296\t<file path=\"src/services/events_service.py\">\n2297\t\"\"\"Service for `POST /v1/events` — the idempotent insert + rollup increment.\n2298\t\n2299\tOrchestrates one PostgreSQL transaction per request: try the insert, and only\n2300\tif it actually landed a new row, upsert the rollup counter. This is the one\n2301\ttransaction the plan's idempotency mechanism depends on for atomicity — see\n2302\t`src/repositories/events_repo.py` for the `ON CONFLICT` primitive itself.\n2303\t\"\"\"\n2304\t⋮----\n2305\tlogger = get_logger(service=\"meterly\")\n2306\t⋮----\n2307\t@dataclass(frozen=True)\n2308\tclass EventCreationOutcome\n2309\t⋮----\n2310\t\"\"\"The result of processing a `POST /v1/events` request: the event\n2311\t    record and the HTTP status the route should return (201 new, 200 replay).\"\"\"\n2312\t⋮----\n2313\trecord: EventRecord\n2314\thttp_status: int\n2315\tidempotent_replay: bool\n2316\t⋮----\n2317\tclass IdempotencyRaceError(RuntimeError)\n2318\t⋮----\n2319\t\"\"\"Raised if a duplicate-key insert lost the race but the original row\n2320\t    can't be found — should be unreachable given the UNIQUE constraint, but\n2321\t    the service fails loudly rather than returning an empty response.\"\"\"\n2322\t⋮----\n2323\tclass QuotaExceededError(AppError)\n2324\t⋮----\n2325\t\"\"\"429 with the distinct `quota_exceeded` app_code (never `rate_limited`,\n2326\t    which already owns 429 for the Tier-2 throttle), carrying `Retry-After`\n2327\t    seconds to the next hour boundary.\n2328\t\n2329\t    Raising this mid-transaction — after the event `INSERT`, before the\n2330\t    rollup increment — is what triggers the rollback that leaves no partial\n2331\t    write behind: propagating out of `scoped_transaction`'s `session.begin()`\n2332\t    context undoes the event row and skips `increment_usage_rollup` entirely.\n2333\t    \"\"\"\n2334\t⋮----\n2335\tdef __init__(self, retry_after_seconds: int) -> None\n2336\t⋮----\n2337\tdef _seconds_until_next_hour_boundary(received_at: datetime, window_start: datetime) -> int\n2338\t⋮----\n2339\t\"\"\"Seconds from `received_at` to the end of `window_start`'s hour,\n2340\t    floored to at least 1 — the `Retry-After` value for a quota rejection.\"\"\"\n2341\tnext_window_start = window_start + timedelta(hours=1)\n2342\t⋮----\n2343\t\"\"\"Record a metered event, idempotent on `(api_key_id, idempotency_key)`.\n2344\t\n2345\t    The server — never the client — sets `api_key_id` (from the authenticated\n2346\t    principal) and `window_start` (the receive time floored to the UTC hour),\n2347\t    which is the mass-assignment protection the plan calls out (ASVS 15.3.3).\n2348\t    \"\"\"\n2349\treceived_at = datetime.now(timezone.utc)\n2350\twindow_start = floor_to_hour_utc(received_at)\n2351\t⋮----\n2352\tinserted = await insert_event_if_new(\n2353\t⋮----\n2354\tquota_state = await read_tenant_quota_state_locked(\n2355\t⋮----\n2356\t# Deliberately omits current_total/limit from both the log and\n2357\t# the (AppError-carried) client envelope — usage totals are\n2358\t# billing-adjacent (plan §\"Info Disclosure\"); the enforcement\n2359\t# event itself is what ops needs (ASVS 16.3.3).\n2360\t⋮----\n2361\toriginal = await find_event_by_idempotency_key(\n2362\t⋮----\n2363\tdef to_response(outcome: EventCreationOutcome) -> EventResponse\n2364\t⋮----\n2365\t\"\"\"Map the service outcome to the minimal public response shape (ASVS 15.3.1).\"\"\"\n2366\trecord = outcome.record\n2367\t</file>\n2368\t\n2369\t<file path=\"src/services/README.md\">\n2370\t# src/services/\n2371\t\n2372\t## Purpose\n2373\t\n2374\tBusiness logic layer: event ingestion (with idempotency and counter atomicity), usage aggregation, and time-window calculations. Orchestrates repositories and enforces domain invariants.\n2375\t\n2376\t## Modules\n2377\t\n2378\t| File / Module | Responsibility |\n2379\t|---|---|\n2380\t| `events_service.py` | `create_event(principal, payload)` — inserts an event, checks the caller's quota (if any) on the winning-insert branch, and increments the hourly counter, all in one transaction; idempotent on `idempotency_key`. Raises `QuotaExceededError` (429 `quota_exceeded`) when `R + Q > L`, which rolls back the event insert. Returns the created/replayed event. |\n2381\t| `usage_service.py` | `read_usage(api_key_id, customer_id, metric, window)` — reads the aggregated counter for a time bucket; returns zeros if the bucket is empty (never 404). |\n2382\t| `quota_service.py` | `upsert_tenant_quota(principal, payload)` — create-or-replaces the caller's cap for `(customer_id, metric)` in one transaction; maps the repository's insert-vs-replace signal to 201/200 and logs the `quota.upsert` audit event. |\n2383\t| `time_windows.py` | `window_start_utc(ts: datetime)` — floors a timezone-aware timestamp to the hour (UTC); used by all three services. |\n2384\t\n2385\t## Relationships\n2386\t\n2387\t**Public surface:**\n2388\t- Imported by `src/api.routes.{events, usage, quotas}` to execute the core business operations.\n2389\t\n2390\t**Dependencies:**\n2391\t- `events_service` imports `src/repositories.{events_repo, quotas_repo}` to insert the event, check the quota, and upsert the counter.\n2392\t- `usage_service` imports `src/repositories.usage_repo` to read the rollup.\n2393\t- `quota_service` imports `src/repositories.quotas_repo` to upsert the cap.\n2394\t- All three services receive an authenticated `AuthenticatedPrincipal` from the route handler (set by `require_api_key` guard); `principal.scope` gates `PUT /v1/quotas` at the route layer before `quota_service` ever runs.\n2395\t- `time_windows` is imported by `events_service` and `usage_service` to floor timestamps.\n2396\t\n2397\t**Transaction boundary:**\n2398\t- `create_event` wraps the event insert, the quota check, and the rollup upsert in one PostgreSQL transaction (via `src/db/session_context`).\n2399\t- This atomicity ensures that if the insert wins (no existing `idempotency_key`) and the quota check passes, the counter increments exactly once.\n2400\t- If the insert loses (duplicate key), the quota is never consulted and neither the counter nor any side effect happens — a no-op.\n2401\t- If the quota check rejects (`R + Q > L`), raising `QuotaExceededError` propagates out of the transaction context and rolls it back — the event insert is undone and the counter is never touched (no partial write).\n2402\t- `upsert_tenant_quota` wraps the quota upsert in its own transaction; a single `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT ... DO UPDATE ... RETURNING (xmax = 0)` reports create-vs-replace with no second round-trip.\n2403\t\n2404\t## Notes\n2405\t\n2406\t**Idempotency guarantee:**\n2407\t- The unique constraint `UNIQUE (api_key_id, idempotency_key)` on the `events` table is the source of truth.\n2408\t- Exactly one of N concurrent identical requests will succeed; the rest get a duplicate-key constraint violation (caught, no exception raised to handler) and fall through to a replay branch.\n2409\t- The replay branch reads the original event from the table and returns it, so the caller sees a consistent result across retries.\n2410\t- Recorded in the plan as the **AC-CONCURRENCY** mechanism: 50 concurrent same-key POSTs produce exactly one row and 49 get the replay response (200 vs. 201).\n2411\t\n2412\t**Counter atomicity:**\n2413\t- The event insert and the rollup upsert are in one transaction, so both commit or both roll back.\n2414\t- This means a counter never gets incremented without the event being persisted (no partial writes).\n2415\t- Also means a duplicate event never increments the counter (no double-counting).\n2416\t- The counter uses `INSERT ... ON CONFLICT ... DO UPDATE` with `total_quantity + EXCLUDED.total_quantity` to handle the increment (PostgreSQL's row-level conflict resolution, atomic at the SQL level).\n2417\t\n2418\t**Time-window semantics:**\n2419\t- A timestamp is floored to its hour (UTC) to get the `window_start`. E.g., `2026-07-06T14:35:42Z` → `2026-07-06T14:00:00Z`.\n2420\t- The floor is done explicitly in Python (`ts.replace(minute=0, second=0, microsecond=0)`) rather than in the database, because PostgreSQL's `date_trunc('hour', ts)` is STABLE (depends on session timezone), not IMMUTABLE, so it cannot be used in a stored generated column.\n2421\t- All windows are in UTC; clients must provide timezone-aware ISO-8601 timestamps on GET.\n2422\t\n2423\t**Scoping by api_key_id:**\n2424\t- Both services receive the authenticated `api_key_id` from the route guard (set in `request.state`).\n2425\t- Both services pass it to the repository layer, which includes it in the WHERE clause (e.g., `WHERE api_key_id = :auth_key AND customer_id = :customer_id`).\n2426\t- This is the primary RLS mechanism; the PostgreSQL RLS policy is the backstop.\n2427\t</file>\n2428\t\n2429\t</files>"}]},"uuid":"bffd6623-23c8-4dc6-86e8-fc2c5936612a","timestamp":"2026-07-09T17:30:47.460Z","sourceToolAssistantUUID":"dfab60a4-dec4-4a42-9a3a-1694384c1863","userType":"external","entrypoint":"claude-vscode","cwd":"C:\\Users\\brett\\OneDrive\\Documents\\GitHub\\meterly-pipeline-test","sessionId":"d6fd840f-4c15-4ec4-8e2b-f4a42b2cbb1a","version":"2.1.204","gitBranch":"feature/usage-export"}
